	(400,'STARS 1.1 & 1.0','2009-11-13 12:14:13',9,'<p><a href=\"#stars_1.0\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.0</a>, which launched on January 19, 2010, after a three-year development process.&nbsp; It is the first version of STARS&nbsp;in which Participants could earn a rating. <a href=\"#stars_1.1\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.1</a> was launched on February 9, 2011.&nbsp; Participants that register for STARS after February 8, 2012 will use <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.2</a>.&nbsp; Institutions that have registered under STARS 1.0, or STARS 1.1, may <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/reporting-and-information-sharing.html#1.1\" target=\"_self\">migrate</a> their data to STARS 1.2.</p>\r\n<!--break-->\r\n<h2><a name=\"stars_1.1\" target=\"_self\"></a>STARS&nbsp;1.1 Technical Manual</h2>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_administrative_update_one_technical_manual.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.1 Administrative Update One</a> (pdf) is the go-to guide for the STARS&nbsp;credits.  The document includes  details about each STARS credit, including the credit criteria, a  description of how points are earned, the reporting fields that Participants complete to document that they earn the credit, guidance on  measurement, relevant definitions, and examples.  In addition, the  document provides background on how the system was developed, how ratings are calculated, and more.</p>\r\n<p>This Administrative Update contains basic system maintenance changes to  STARS 1.1, such as additional language to clarify credits and correction  of typographical errors. These changes do not change any credits  substantively and do not change credit scoring. View the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_administrative_update_one_record_of_changes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">September 2011 Record of Changes</a> which outline the edits made between STARS 1.1 and STARS 1.1 Administrative Update One.</p>\r\n<p>Participants who have used an earlier version may wish to consult the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/1.1_record_of_changes_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"February 2011 Record of Changes\">February 2011 Record of Changes</a> (pdf), which details the differences between the STARS 1.0 Administrative Update Two version and STARS 1.1 version. New STARS Participants should use the most recent version of the Technical Manual. All institutions registering after February 9, 2011 will be using STARS 1.1. Institutions that have been using STARS 1.0 will have the option to migrate their data into STARS 1.1.</p>\r\n<p>The STARS 1.1 Credit Checklist provides a quick snapshot of the credits included in STARS&nbsp;1.1. Download a <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_credit_checklist.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"Credit Checklist PDF\">PDF&nbsp;version</a> (pdf) or <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_credit_checklist.xls\" target=\"_self\" title=\"Credit Checklist XLS\">Excel version</a> (xls).</p>\r\n<h2><a name=\"stars_1.0\" target=\"_self\"></a>STARS&nbsp;1.0 Technical Manual</h2>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.0_technical_manual_admin_update_2.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;1.0 Technical Manual Administrative Update Two</a> (pdf) is the go-to guide for the STARS 1.0 credits.The current version, which was launched February 9, 2011, is <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.1</a>. The document includes details about each STARS 1.0 credit, including the credit criteria, a description of how points are earned, the reporting fields that Participants complete to document that they earn the credit, guidance on measurement, relevant definitions, and examples.  In addition, the document provides background on how the system was developed, how ratings are calculated, and more.</p>\r\n<p>While no major changes were made to the STARS&nbsp;1.0 credits, it was revised several times. Participants who have used an earlier version may wish to consult the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Technical_Manual_Changes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">January 2010 Record of Changes</a> (pdf), which details the differences between the Early Release (9/2009) version and the 1.0 edition (1/2010);&nbsp; the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_1.0_Admin_Update_One.pdf\" target=\"_self\">June 2010 Record of Changes</a> (pdf), which details the differences between the 1.0 edition (1/2010) edition and the Administrative Update One edition (6/2010); and the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/1.0.2_Record_of_Changes_05Nov10.pdf\" target=\"_self\">November 2010 Record of Changes</a> (pdf), which details the differences between the Administrative Update One edition and the Administrative Update Two edition.</p>\r\n<p>The STARS 1.0 Credit Checklist provides a quick snapshot of the credits included in STARS&nbsp;1.0. Download a <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_1.0_Credit_List.pdf\" target=\"_self\">PDF&nbsp;version</a> (pdf) or <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_1.0_credit_list.xls\" target=\"_self\">Excel version</a> (xls).</p>\r\n<h2>How Credits Were Developed and Weighted</h2>\r\n<div style=\"float: right; padding: 5px; margin: 12px; width: 200px; border: 1px solid #aaa;\">\r\n<p><em><strong>Gatekeeper Questions</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em>What does it take for a credit to be included in STARS? Each STARS credit was vetted using the following questions:</em></p>\r\n<p><em>1. Does the credit speak to improved environmental, social, and/or financial impacts?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>2. Is the credit relevant and meaningful for diverse institutions?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>3. If the credit is based on the presence of a strategy, is a performance-based indicator not available or appropriate?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>4. Is the credit measurable, objective, and actionable?</em></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>STARS credits were developed in large part by reviewing campus sustainability assessments, sustainability reports from businesses, and other sustainability rating and ranking systems. For STARS 1.0 the initial credits from the STARS Pilot were revised or eliminated and new credits were added based on feedback from hundreds of diverse stakeholders and experts. In addition, STARS credits were vetted using four criteria.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>In order to be included, each credit must lead to improved environmental, social, and/or economic performance by colleges and universities. While the sphere of impact may vary each credit should indicate a movement toward sustainability.</li>\r\n<li>Given the diversity of higher education institutions, each STARS credit should be appropriate for most institution types. In order to accommodate this diversity, some STARS credits do not include detailed specifications but are instead flexible or open. In other cases, credits include an applicability criterion, so that the credit only applies to certain types of institutions.</li>\r\n<li>STARS strives to prioritize performance over strategy when possible. Performance credits are based on measurements of sustainability performance while strategy credits focus on approaches or processes that can help improve an institution\'s performance. In many instances, however, measurable, meaningful, and fairly comparable performance indicators could not be identified, so a strategy-based credit was used. As a result, both strategy and performance credits have a place in the system.</li>\r\n<li>AASHE strived to ensure that each credit was objective, measurable, and actionable.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Points were allocated using the following considerations:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>To what extent does the credit contribute to improved environmental impacts?</li>\r\n<li>To what extent does the credit contribute to improved financial impacts?</li>\r\n<li>To what extent does the credit contribute to improved social impacts?</li>\r\n<li>To what extent are there educational benefits associated with the achievement of this credit?                                    \r\n<ul type=\"circle\">\r\n<li>How many people are impacted (breadth)?&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>How deeply are people impacted (depth)?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Tier One and Tier Two Credits</h2>\r\n<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n<p>Each STARS credit that meets these four criteria listed above (see also &ldquo;gatekeeper questions&rdquo; textbox) is classified as Tier One or Tier Two.&nbsp; The differences between Tier One and Tier Two credits are outlined below:</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\"><strong>Tier One</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\"><strong>Tier Two</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Strive to capture measurable outcome</li>\r\n<li><span>Vary in the number of points they are worth</span></li>\r\n<li><span><span>Grouped in a subcategory (e.g. Curriculum) within a category (e.g. Education &amp; Research)</span><br /></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Acknowledge strategies and tend to have a smaller impact than Tier One credits</li>\r\n<li><span>Promote strategies whose benefits are already captured by a Tier One credit</span></li>\r\n<li><span><span>Worth 0.25 points each</span><br /></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>',1,'stars-10','<p>STARS 1.0, which launched on January 19, 2010, after a three-year development process.&nbsp; It is the first version of STARS&nbsp;in which Participants could earn a rating.</p>',3993,'2013-08-01 11:39:42'),
