	(100,'Program Overview','2009-12-02 12:08:09',18,'<!--break-->\r\n<p><a href=\"#what_stars\" target=\"_self\">What is STARS?</a><br /> <a href=\"#goals\" target=\"_self\">What are the goals of STARS? </a><br /> <a href=\"#benefits\" target=\"_self\">What are the benefits of participating in STARS?</a><br /> <a href=\"#organized\" target=\"_self\">How is STARS&nbsp;organized?</a></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"what_stars\" target=\"_self\"></a></strong><strong>What is STARS?</strong><br /> STARS is an innovative, voluntary self-reporting framework for colleges and universities to gauge progress toward sustainability and be recognized for sustainability leadership.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"goals\" target=\"_self\"></a><strong>What are the goals of STARS?<br /> </strong> <strong> </strong>STARS is designed to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span>Provide a guide for advancing sustainability in all sectors of higher education, from education and research to operations and administration.</span></li>\r\n<li><span>Enable meaningful comparisons over time and across institutions by establishing a common standard of measurement for sustainability in higher education.</span></li>\r\n<li><span> Create incentives for continual improvement toward sustainability.</span></li>\r\n<li><span> Facilitate information sharing about higher education sustainability practices and performance.</span></li>\r\n<li><span> Build a stronger, more diverse campus sustainability community and promote a comprehensive understanding of sustainability that includes its social, economic and environmental dimensions.</span>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"benefits\" target=\"_self\"></a>What are the benefits of participating in STARS?</strong><br /> There are several <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/stars-participant-benefits.html\" target=\"_self\">benefits</a> associated with being a STARS Participant. STARS will help schools set and meet sustainability goals and will foster information sharing about practices and performance among the campus sustainability community. All schools that participate in STARS will receive positive recognition. Schools that register now will be recognized as STARS Participants. Being able to claim a STARS rating can help an institution reap marketing and recruitment benefits of sustainability leadership.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"organized\" target=\"_self\"></a>How is STARS organized? </strong><br /> Institutions earn points in three main categories: Education &amp; Research; Operations; and Planning, Administration &amp; Engagement. Each of these categories includes subcategories such as Purchasing, Curriculum, Energy, and Human Resources. There is also an Innovation category to recognize pioneering practices that aren&rsquo;t covered by other STARS credits.</p>\r\n<p>See a <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_common_definitions_external.pdf\" target=\"_self\">list</a> (pdf) of common STARS terms and definitions.</p>',1,'program-overview','<p>What is STARS? <br /> What are the goals of STARS? <br /> What are the benefits of participating in STARS? <br /> How is STARS organized?</p>',4101,'2012-05-08 16:12:46'),
	(102,'STARS History and System Development','2009-12-02 12:12:36',19,'<!--break-->\r\n<p><a href=\"#developed\" target=\"_self\">How was STARS developed? </a><br /> <a href=\"#social\" target=\"_self\">Why does STARS include &ldquo;social&rdquo; indicators? Isn&rsquo;t sustainability mostly about the environment? </a><br /> <a href=\"#differences\" target=\"_self\">What are the main differences between the credits in the STARS Pilot and STARS 1.0?</a><br /> <a href=\"#how_updated\" target=\"_self\">How will the system be updated?</a><br /> <a href=\"#when_updated\" target=\"_self\">When will the system be updated?</a></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"developed\" target=\"_self\"></a>How was STARS developed?</strong><br /> In 2006 the Higher Education Associations\' Sustainability Consortium (HEASC), an informal network of higher education associations with a commitment to sustainability, issued <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/HEASCcall.pdf\" target=\"_self\">a call for a campus sustainability rating system</a> (pdf). Since then, AASHE has worked collaboratively with other non-profits and higher education associations on the development of STARS. A Steering Committee, Strategic Advisory Committee, and a Technical Advisory Committee weighed in on the system and nearly 70 institutions participated in a year-long pilot program.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"social\" target=\"_self\"></a>Why does STARS include &ldquo;social&rdquo; indicators? Isn&rsquo;t sustainability mostly about the environment? </strong><br /> The most commonly used definition of sustainability&ndash;meeting the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs&ndash;is from <em>Our Common Future: The Report of the World Commission on Environment and Development</em>, commonly known as the Brundtland Commission report. The interconnectedness and interdependence of the social, environmental, and economic dimensions of sustainability are included throughout <em>Our Common Future</em>. The Brundtland Commission writes, &ldquo;our inability to promote the common interest in sustainable development is often a product of the relative neglect of economic and social justice.&rdquo; The report continues, &ldquo;[a] world in which poverty and inequity are endemic will always be prone to ecological and other crises. Sustainable development requires meeting the basic needs of all and extending to all the opportunity to satisfy their aspirations for a better life.&rdquo; And, \"[e]ven the narrow notion of physical sustainability implies a concern for social equity between generations, a concern that must logically be extended to equity within each generation.\"</p>\r\n<p>Many popular uses of and references to sustainability also emphasize the concept&rsquo;s economic, environmental, and social dimensions. For example, businesses talk about the triple bottom line: people, planet, and profits (or, alternately, human capital, natural capital, and financial capital). Likewise, sustainability educators commonly refer to the Three Es of sustainability: economy, ecology, and equity. Similarly, popular representations of sustainability underscore the concept&rsquo;s three dimensions. Sustainability experts often use a three-legged stool as a symbol for sustainability. The social, economic, and environmental components of sustainability each represent one of the stool&rsquo;s legs. If one of the legs is missing, the stool cannot balance or function. Another common illustration of sustainability is a diagram depicting three overlapping circles, representing environmental needs, economic needs and social needs. The area where the circles overlap and all three needs are met is the area of sustainability.</p>\r\n<p>STARS represents an attempt to translate this broad and inclusive view of sustainability to measurable objectives at the campus level. Thus, it includes credits related to an institution&rsquo;s environmental, social, and economic performance.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"differences\" target=\"_self\"></a>What are the main differences between the STARS Pilot and STARS 1.0?</strong><br /> First, some credits&ndash;particularly those for which gathering data proved especially difficult or impossible&ndash;have been eliminated.  In addition, STARS 1.0 does not include prerequisites.</p>\r\n<p>Second, additional definitions and guidelines have been added to many credits in an effort to make the credit criteria clearer.</p>\r\n<p>Third, for the first time, AASHE has gone through a deliberate credit weighting or point allocation exercise.  In other words, the point value assigned to each credit has been evaluated relative to other credits such that the credits that have the greatest impact on an institutions&rsquo; sustainability performance are worth the most points.</p>\r\n<p>Fourth, many credits have been restructured such that partial points are available.  This approach better recognizes incremental change and creates a stronger incentive for continued progress toward sustainability.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"how_updated\" target=\"_self\"></a>How will the system be updated?</strong><br /> AASHE will continue to work with STARS participants and the campus sustainability community to improve the system.  Comments or feedback on STARS may be sent to the STARS staff at any time (<a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">stars@aashe.org</a>).  Before a new version (e.g., STARS 2.0) is released, AASHE will hold a public comment period to allow stakeholders an opportunity to comment on proposed changes. View details about the development process and timeline in the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/technical_development_policy.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Technical Development Policy</a> (pdf).</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"when_updated\" target=\"_self\"></a>When will the system be updated?</strong><br /> Major changes to the system will likely occur every two or three years.   In the mean time, AASHE may make small changes and clarifying edits to the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a> to respond to participants&rsquo; needs.&nbsp; View <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/technical_development_policy.pdf\" target=\"_self\">details about the development process and timeline</a> (pdf).&nbsp;</p>',1,'stars-history-and-system-development','<p>How was STARS developed?<br /> Why does STARS include &ldquo;social&rdquo; indicators? Isn&rsquo;t sustainability mostly about the environment?<br /> What are the main differences between the credits in the STARS Pilot and STARS 1.0?<br /> How will the system be updated?<br /> When will the system be updated?</p>',4102,'2012-07-20 14:39:19'),
	(104,'Participation','2009-12-02 12:17:52',20,'<!--break-->\r\n<p><a href=\"#who_participate\" target=\"_self\">Who can participate in STARS?</a><br /> <a href=\"#system\" target=\"_self\">Can an entire university system register?</a><br /> <a href=\"#submit\" target=\"_self\">How often can an institution submit for a STARS Rating? </a><br /> <a href=\"#fee\" target=\"_self\">How much does it cost to participate?</a><br /> <a href=\"#member\" target=\"_self\">Why must AASHE member campuses pay an additional fee to participate in STARS?</a><br /> <a href=\"#How_long\" target=\"_self\">How long do institutions have to complete STARS?</a><a href=\"#extend_deadline\" target=\"_self\"><br /> </a><a href=\"#technical_manual\" target=\"_self\">Will campuses be able to see the STARS criteria before signing up to be a Participant?</a><br /> <a href=\"#register_participant\" target=\"_self\">How do I register to become a STARS Participant?</a><br /> <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/participation.html#Reporter\" target=\"_self\">What is the difference between a &ldquo;Charter Participant&rdquo; and a regular &ldquo;Participant&rdquo;?<br /></a><a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/participation.html#Reporter\" target=\"_self\">Can an institution participate in STARS without being scored?</a></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"who_participate\" target=\"_self\"></a>Who can participate in STARS? </strong><br /> Any college or university located in the U.S. or Canada may participate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>STARS provides a framework for institutions taking first steps toward  sustainability as well as established sustainability leaders. An institution is defined by having a separate and distinct administration (e.g. president or chancellor). For an institution which may be a part of a larger system, it must have an administration that is separate and distinct from others in the system of which it is a part.</p>\r\n<p>If an institution or entity does not meet these requirements, but you believe that you have a compelling case for the participation of that institution or entity in STARS, please complete the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/cfm/eligibility-inquiry/\" target=\"_self\">Eligibility Inquiry Form</a>. This information will be evaluated by the STARS staff, who will decide if the institution or entity is eligible to participate in STARS.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"system\" target=\"_self\"></a>Can an entire university system register?</strong><br /> Yes, university systems or community college districts may register and report as one entity.  However, AASHE expects that most participants will be individual institutions.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"submit\" target=\"_self\"></a>How often can an institution submit for a STARS Rating? </strong><br />An institution that registers for STARS gains 12-months of continual access to the STARS Reporting Tool and may submit for a STARS rating once during this 12-month period. &nbsp;A STARS rating is valid for three years. &nbsp;After three years, institutions will need to submit a subsequent STARS Report to claim a valid rating.&nbsp;Institutions may submit for a subsequent rating by renewing membership at any time, provided that all&nbsp;<a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/stars-report-accuracy.html\" target=\"_self\">data accuracy mechanisms</a> are followed. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"fee\" target=\"_self\"></a>How much will it cost to participate?</strong><br /> STARS registration fees:<br /> AASHE Member.......................................$900<br /> Non-Member...........................................$1,400</p>\r\n<p>Discount for renewing STARS Participants:<br /> AASHE Member &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;......................$450<br /> Non-Member &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;.&hellip;&hellip;......................$700</p>\r\n<p>The STARS fee is due at the time of your institution\'s registration for STARS.  Once your institution has paid the STARS registration fee, data collection and documentation in the STARS Reporting Tool may begin. Access to the Reporting Tool will continue for 12 months. No additional fees are required to complete your submission.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>AASHE encourages institutions to participate in STARS on an annual basis. Any institution that registers for STARS within 90 days of its subscription expiration date will be eligible for the 50% discount (i.e.  $450 for AASHE members and $700 for non-members).</p>\r\n<p>For more information about <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/membership\" target=\"_self\">AASHE Membership</a>, please visit the AASHE <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/\" target=\"_self\">website</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"member\" target=\"_self\"></a>Why must AASHE member campuses pay an additional fee to participate in STARS?</strong><br /> STARS is a program of AASHE that is open to all institutions.  AASHE member institutions receive a discount.  AASHE instituted a fee for STARS to pay for the costs of continued development and maintenance of the rating system, including the online Reporting Tool (available only to STARS participants) and new resources for participants.  AASHE income and expenditure figures, including those related to STARS, are posted in the annual budget, which can be downloaded from our <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/about/governance-documents\" target=\"_self\">governance page</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"How_long\" target=\"_self\"></a>How long do institutions have to complete STARS?</strong><br /> STARS Participants receive 12-months of continuous access to the STARS  Reporting Tool and are encouraged to submit their STARS Report during  this time frame. Once a STARS Participant submits its STARS Report and  earns a STARS rating, this rating is valid for three years.&nbsp; However,  STARS Participants are encouraged to <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/registration.html\" target=\"_self\">participate in STARS</a> on an annual  basis and have the opportunity to do so, at a discounted rate, so they  can continue tracking their STARS data.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"technical_manual\" target=\"_self\"></a>Will campuses be able to see the STARS criteria before signing up to be a Participant?</strong><br /> Yes, the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a>, which outlines all of the details of the STARS&nbsp;credits, is publicly available.<strong><br /> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"register_participant\" target=\"_self\"></a>How do I register to become a STARS Participant?</strong><br /> You can&nbsp;<a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/4269/?root_category=get-involved\" target=\"_self\">register online</a> and payments can be made either online or by check (mailed to AASHE&rsquo;s office). At registration, the registrant will be asked for the name and contact information for your primary STARS Liaison as well as your Executive Contact (president, vice president, provost, chancellor, etc.) who will be included on an email confirming your institution&rsquo;s STARS registration.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"difference\" target=\"_self\"></a>What is the difference between a &ldquo;Charter Participant&rdquo; and a regular &ldquo;Participant&rdquo;?</strong><br /> A STARS Charter Participant is an institution that registered to use STARS between September 20, 2009, and August 20, 2010. Charter participants will be recognized in STARS publicity and on the STARS website. Institutions that register for STARS after August 20, 2010, will be referred to as STARS &ldquo;Participants\"</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"Reporter\" target=\"_self\"></a>Can an institution participate in STARS without being scored?</strong><br /> An institution that wishes to participate in STARS but does not want their scores to be public, may earn recognition through the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/rating.html#reporter\" target=\"_self\">STARS Reporter</a> rating. These institutions receive the same benefits as institutions that pursue any other STARS rating, including positive recognition for participation and the ability to share data publicly. After seeing their final score, all participants are able to choose STARS Reporter status before completing their final submission and making it public.</p>',1,'participation','<p>Who can participate in STARS?<br /> Can an entire university system register?<br /> How often can an institution submit for a STARS Rating?<br /> How much does it cost to participate?<br /> Why must AASHE member campuses pay an additional fee to participate in STARS?<br /> How long do institutions have to complete STARS?<br /> How do I extend my STARS submission deadline?<br /> Will campuses be able to see the STARS criteria before signing up to be a Participant?<br /> How do I register to become a STARS Participant?<br /> What is the difference between a &ldquo;Charter Participant&rdquo; and a regular &ldquo;Participant&rdquo;?<br />Can an institution participate in STARS without being scored?</p>',4103,'2013-01-02 12:31:36'),
	(0,'My Resources','2012-03-21 14:24:13',83,'<h2>STARS Visuals &amp; Terms</h2>\r\n<p>Participants may wish to consult the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/brand_guidelines-embedded.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Brand Guidelines</a> (pdf) for guidance on using the STARS logo and seals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>View a <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_common_definitions_external.pdf\" target=\"_self\">list</a> (pdf) of common STARS terms and definitions.</p>\r\n<h2>Data Collection Tools</h2>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.2_data_tracking.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.2 Data Tracking Spreadsheet</a> (xls) outlines the credits within each category and the reporting fields for each credit. Data tracking  spreadsheets for <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_admin_update_one_data_tracking.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;1.1.1</a> (xls) and  <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.0_data_tracking.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.0</a> (xls) are also available. <em>Please note</em>: This optional resource is provided to help organize your institution\'s data collection process; all data will need to be saved in the online Reporting Tool in order to report officially. Participants are encouraged to use the Reporting Tool throughout the data collection process.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To facilitate the data collection process, Word versions of the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.2.docx\" target=\"_self\"> STARS 1.2</a> (doc),&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_admin_update_one_technical_manual-credits_only.doc\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;1.1 Administrative Update One credits</a> (doc), and the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.0_technical_manual_admin_update_2-credits_only.docx\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;1.0 credits</a> (doc) are available for download. You may also download the most recent version of the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">Technical Manual</a> on the STARS website. <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/history/\" target=\"_self\">Earlier versions</a> are available on the website as well.</p>\r\n<h2>Template Emails</h2>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/announcing_stars_to_your_institution_email_template_2.8.11.doc\" target=\"_self\">Announcing STARS&nbsp;to&nbsp;Your Institution Email Template</a> (doc)</p>\r\n<p>The intention of this email template is to announce your  institution\'s participation in STARS&nbsp;to campus stakeholders and notify  these individuals that they may be contacted for information regarding  the STARS&nbsp;credits. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/colleague_outreach_email_template_2.8.11.doc\" target=\"_self\">Colleague Outreach Email Template</a> (doc)</p>\r\n<p>Participants may modify this email template to connect with  colleagues at other institutions that are not yet participating in the  STARS&nbsp;program.&nbsp; The Colleague Outreach Email Template details the  benefits of the STARS program and encourages registration.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/requesting_departmental_data_for_stars_email_template_2.8.11.doc\" target=\"_self\">Requesting Departmental Data for STARS&nbsp;Email&nbsp;Template</a> (doc)</p>\r\n<p>This email template was designed to assist STARS&nbsp;Liaisons in the data  collection process and may be used to request information for specific  STARS credits from campus stakeholders.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/responsible_party_email_template.doc\" target=\"_self\">Responsible Party Email Template</a> (doc)</p>\r\n<p>AASHE recommends each Responsible Party listed in the STARS Reporting Tool is notified.&nbsp; This email template gives a brief explanation of the STARS Program while also explaining the role of the individual that is identified as a Responsible Party.</p>\r\n<h2>Innovation Inventory</h2>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_innovation_inventory_process_procedures.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Innovation Inventory Process &amp; Procedures</a> (pdf)</p>\r\n<p>This document details the processes and procedures for conducting the STARS Innovation Inventory, listed below.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/innovation_database_6.1.12.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS Innovation Inventory 6.1.12</a>&nbsp;- (xls)</p>\r\n<p>The STARS Innovation Inventory was created to effectively manage the large amount of information within the Innovation (IN) category of STARS. The current version of the inventory includes all STARS reports submitted through June 1, 2012. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Additional Resources</h2>\r\n<p>The following resources have been provided by institutions considering participating in STARS, STARS&nbsp;Participants, and Partner Organizations. These resources were created in the context of a specific version of STARS, as indicated. Versions of the STARS Technical Manual vary, so you may find it necessary to adjust the resources slightly to align them with the version of STARS you are using. For additional resources on campus sustainability, visit AASHE\'s <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/resources\" target=\"_self\">Campus Sustainability Resource Center</a>. To submit a resource to be posted here please contact <a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">stars@aashe.org</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>STARS 1.2</strong></p>\r\n<p>California State University, Chico<br /> Provided by <a href=\"mailto:falexander@csuchico.edu\" target=\"_self\">Fletcher Alexander</a></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/step_by_step_filing_of_credits_csu_chico_11.10.11.docx\" target=\"_self\">Instructions for Documenting STARS Credits</a>&nbsp;(docx)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_reporter_cover_letter_csu_chico_11.10.11.docx\" target=\"_self\">Welcome Letter to STARS Reporting Tool Users</a> (docx)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Seattle University<br /> Provided by <a href=\"mailto:kprice@seattleu.edu\" target=\"_self\">Karen Price</a></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_credit_checklist_template.xls\" target=\"_self\"> STARS Credit Checklist Template</a> (pdf)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>STARS 1.1</strong></p>\r\n<p>Responsible Endowments Coalition<br /> Provided by <a href=\"mailto:dan@endowmentethics.org\" target=\"_self\">Dan Apfel</a></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_sustainable_investment_guide.pdf\" target=\"_self\"> STARS Sustainable Investment Guide</a> (pdf)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_sustainable_investment_guide_worksheet.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS Sustainable Investment Guide Worksheet</a> (xls)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>STARS 1.0</strong></p>\r\n<p>California State University, Channel Islands<br /> Provided by <a href=\"mailto:laurel.replogle909@csuci.edu\" target=\"_self\">Laurel Replogle</a>.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS%20Operations%20Category%20Tracking%20Spreadsheet_CSU%20Channel%20Islands.accdb\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;Operations Category Tracking Spreadsheet</a> (accdb)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>San Diego State University<br /> Provided by <a href=\"mailto:sd.campbell23@gmail.com\" target=\"_self\">Sarah Campbell</a> and <a href=\"mailto:mhudson@mail.sdsu.edu\" target=\"_self\">Mariah Hudson.</a></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/SDSU%20STARS%20Faculty%20Survey%20Questions.doc\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;Faculty Survey Questions</a> (doc)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>University of California, San Diego<br /> Provided by Maggie Souder. &nbsp;Contact <a href=\"mailto:krhansen@ucsd.edu\" target=\"_self\">Kristin Hanson</a> for more information.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Contacts%20Tracking%20Spreadsheet_UCSD.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;Contact Tracking Spreadsheet</a> (xls)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS%20Education%20and%20Research%20spreadsheet%20for%20key%20stakeholder_UCSD.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS Education &amp;&nbsp;Research Spreadsheet for Key Stakeholders</a> (xls)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS%20Operations%20spreadsheet%20for%20key%20stakeholder_UCSC.xls\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;Operations Spreadsheet for Key Stakeholders</a> (xls)&nbsp; </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>STARS Promotional Tools</h2>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_overview_presentation.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;Overview Presentation</a> (pdf) highlights the details of the STARS&nbsp;program.&nbsp; Use this resource to share information about the STARS&nbsp;program with your institution.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_brochure_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Brochure</a> (pdf) and <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_flyer_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Flyer</a> (pdf) are documents created by AASHE with the intention of sharing a  brief snapshot of the STARS Program including benefits and how the  program works.&nbsp; Both resources may be shared with your colleagues,  community members, and campus to communicate information about the STARS  Program.</p>\r\n<p>The STARS Flyer is a one-page document while the STARS Brochure is a  two-page document where each page is intended to be printed back-to-back  on a single sheet of paper and folded.&nbsp; Please see the STARS Brochure <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/flyer_brochure_instructions_final_1.pdf\" target=\"_self\">printing instructions</a> (pdf).</p>\r\n<h2>Stay Connected</h2>\r\n<p>Subscribe to the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/connect/enewsletters\" target=\"_self\">AASHE newsletters</a> to stay connected to the most current information on sustainability in higher education, including STARS.&nbsp;</p>',1,'my-resources','',NULL,'2013-06-12 14:24:57'),
	(106,'Reporting and Information Sharing','2009-12-02 12:19:39',21,'<!--break-->\r\n<p><a href=\"#getting_started\" target=\"_self\">How do I get started with STARS after I successfully register as a STARS Participant?</a><br /> <a href=\"#migrate\" target=\"_self\">What does it mean to migrate data and how does the migration function work?</a><br /> <a href=\"#migration_options\" target=\"_self\">What is the difference between &lsquo;Version Migration&rsquo; and &lsquo;Data Migration\'?</a><br /> <a href=\"#sharing_data\" target=\"_self\">How do I share my STARS data with Sierra magazine and The Princeton Review to be considered for their publications?</a><br /><a href=\"#demonstrate\" target=\"_self\">How can institutions demonstrate they have earned a credit?</a><br /><a href=\"#timeframe\" target=\"_self\">What timeframe should I use when reporting data for STARS?</a><br /><a href=\"#letter\" target=\"_self\">What should the President\'s Letter include and where do I upload it in the STARS Reporting Tool?</a><br /><a href=\"#public\" target=\"_self\">Will the STARS data be made public? </a><br /><a href=\"#disclose\" target=\"_self\">What  if institutions don\'t want to disclose certain information or make it  publicly available (investment information, for example) or if an  institution just wants to post one of the sections?</a><br /><a href=\"#Erroneous_Data\" target=\"_self\">If I believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I report it?</a><br /><a href=\"#Correct_Information\" target=\"_self\">How do I correct information in my institution\'s STARS Report after the information has been made public?</a><br /><a href=\"#logo\" target=\"_self\">Can I use the STARS logo?</a><br /><a href=\"#1.1\" target=\"_self\">Our institution is currently registered for STARS 1.0 or STARS 1.1 and we noticed that a new version of STARS (1.2) has been launched. How are we affected by the release of STARS 1.2?<br /></a><a href=\"#subsequent\" target=\"_self\">Are there any special considerations for institutions submitting subsequent reports?</a><a href=\"#1.1\" target=\"_self\"></a></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"getting_started\" target=\"_self\"></a>How do I get started with STARS after I successfully register as a STARS Participant?</strong><br /> Visit the \"<a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/help/getting-started/\" target=\"_self\">Getting Started</a>\" section of the STARS \"<a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/help/\" target=\"_self\">Help</a>\" webpage for steps outlining the details of the STARS process from once your institution registers for STARS to after it submits a STARS Report and earns a rating.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"migrate\" target=\"_self\"></a>What does it mean to migrate data and how does the migration function work?</strong><br /> Institutions working in the STARS Reporting Tool will have the opportunity to migrate data.&nbsp; &ldquo;Version Migrations&rdquo; allow an institution to migrate between different versions of the STARS Technical Manual.&nbsp; &ldquo;Data Migrations&rdquo; allow STARS Participants to migrate previously saved data sets into the STARS Reporting Tool.</p>\r\n<p>STARS Participants seeking to migrate data will use the migration function in the STARS Reporting Tool by navigating to the \'My Summary\' page and choosing the \'Migrate\' tab.&nbsp; Please note that it may take a few minutes for migration to complete, during which time the \'My Submission\' section of the Reporting Tool will be locked. Migrating data will replace any previously saved data and all credits are marked as &ldquo;In Progress&rdquo; after migration is complete.&nbsp; Changes to credit status must be done manually.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"migration_options\" target=\"_self\"></a>What is the difference between &lsquo;Version Migration&rsquo; and &lsquo;Data Migration\'?</strong><br /> \'Version Migrations\' allow an institution to migrate between different versions of the STARS Technical Manual.&nbsp; For example, an institution may have registered under a version of STARS, such as 1.1, but during the institution\'s subscription to the STARS Reporting Tool another version of STARS was launched, such as 1.2.&nbsp; Completing a \'Version Migration\' will allow the institution to update credits that are outlined in the \'My Submission\' section of the STARS Reporting Tool so that this information reflects the most current version of the STARS credits. Data saved in the STARS Reporting Tool prior to the migration will be visible in the Reporting Tool once the migration is complete.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Data Migrations&rdquo; allow STARS Participants to migrate previously saved data sets into the STARS Reporting Tool. For example, institutions may choose to pull data from a previously submitted STARS Report, or saved snapshot, into the STARS Reporting Tool. Completing a \'Data Migration\' will allow the institution to work off of the specific data set that is moved into the STARS Reporting Tool instead of documenting data from scratch. Migrating data  will replace any previously saved data.</p>\r\n<p><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <o:DocumentProperties> <o:Revision>0</o:Revision> <o:TotalTime>0</o:TotalTime> <o:Pages>1</o:Pages> <o:Words>75</o:Words> <o:Characters>433</o:Characters> <o:Company>AASHE</o:Company> <o:Lines>3</o:Lines> <o:Paragraphs>1</o:Paragraphs> <o:CharactersWithSpaces>507</o:CharactersWithSpaces> <o:Version>14.0</o:Version> </o:DocumentProperties> <o:OfficeDocumentSettings> <o:AllowPNG /> </o:OfficeDocumentSettings> </xml><![endif]--> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:WordDocument> <w:View>Normal</w:View> <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom> <w:TrackMoves /> <w:TrackFormatting /> <w:PunctuationKerning /> <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas /> <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid> <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent> <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText> <w:DoNotPromoteQF /> <w:LidThemeOther>EN