 UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium List 2 Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"67\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 1 Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"68\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 2 Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"69\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 3 Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"70\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"19\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Emphasis\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"21\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Emphasis\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"31\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Reference\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"32\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Reference\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"33\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Book Title\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"37\" Name=\"Bibliography\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"TOC Heading\" /> </w:LatentStyles> </xml><![endif]--> <!--[if gte mso 10]> <mce:style><!   /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable 	{mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\"; 	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; 	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0; 	mso-style-noshow:yes; 	mso-style-priority:99; 	mso-style-parent:\"\"; 	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt; 	mso-para-margin:0in; 	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt; 	mso-pagination:widow-orphan; 	font-size:12.0pt; 	font-family:Cambria; 	mso-ascii-font-family:Cambria; 	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin; 	mso-hansi-font-family:Cambria; 	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;} --> <!--[endif] --> <!--StartFragment--></p>\r\n<p>STARS Participants seeking to migrate data will use the migration function in the STARS Reporting Tool by navigating to the \'My Summary\' page and choosing the \'Migrate\' tab.&nbsp; Please note that it may take a few minutes for a migration to complete, during which time the \'My Submission\' section of the Reporting Tool will be locked. Migrating data will replace any previously saved data and all credits are marked as &ldquo;In Progress&rdquo; after migration is complete.&nbsp; Changes to credit status must be done manually.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"sharing_data\" target=\"_self\"></a>How do I share my STARS data with Sierra magazine and The Princeton Review to be considered for their publications?</strong><br /> STARS Participants seeking to share data with other organizations must take a snapshot of the data documented in the STARS Reporting Tool and share this  information. Instructions for  taking and sharing snapshots of data are outlined in  the \"Share Data\"  tab of the \"My Summary\" section in the STARS Reporting  Tool.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"#1.1\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></a><strong><a name=\"demonstrate\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How can institutions demonstrate that they earn a credit? </strong><br /> There are specific reporting fields that institutions complete to demonstrate that they earn STARS credits.  These reporting fields are outlined in the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a>. All information is submitted to AASHE through an online <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/tool/\" target=\"_self\">Reporting Tool</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"timeframe\" target=\"_blank\"></a>What timeframe should I use when reporting data for STARS?</strong><br /> Some credits are based on current practices and others are based on historical performance. The <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a> includes guidance on what timeframe to use for each credit. For credits that are based on historical data, schools can choose the timeframe for each credit separately; there is no requirement that an institution use the same time period to gather data for all credits. The key requirement for credits that use annual data is that the data are drawn from a consecutive 12-month period.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"letter\" target=\"_blank\"></a>What should the President\'s Letter include and where do I upload it in the STARS Reporting Tool?</strong><br /> Each submittal for a STARS rating must be accompanied by a letter  from the institution\'s president, chancellor, or highest ranking executive that affirms the accuracy  of the institution\'s STARS Submission. In addition, the president or  chancellor\'s letter serves as an introduction or cover letter for the  submission. As such, the letter may also include a description of the  institution\'s commitment to sustainability, background about the  institution, key achievements or highlights from the STARS submission,  and goals for future submissions. Sign-off from the institution\'s  president or chancellor is an important strategy for promoting accuracy  within the STARS self-assessment framework.</p>\r\n<p>When an institution chooses the button to \"Submit for Rating\" in the  STARS Reporting Tool, the institution will be prompted to upload a PDF  version of the letter from the president or chancellor in the second  step of the submission process. Please allow for adequate time to secure the letter before submitting for a rating.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"public\" target=\"_blank\"></a>Will the STARS data be made public?</strong><br /> Once data documentation in the STARS Reporting Tool is complete, and the data are submitted to AASHE, the institution will earn the STARS rating it achieved and its STARS Report will become public on the STARS website. All data submitted in the institutions STARS Report will be public except for the \"Internal Notes\" section of each credit. During the pilot period, all information  was kept confidential.  Review the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_Pilot_Results_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Pilot Project Results</a> (pdf) for outcomes from the pilot.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"disclose\" target=\"_blank\"></a>What if institutions don\'t want to disclose certain information or make it publicly available (investment information, for example) or if an institution just wants to post one of the sections? </strong><br /> Participation in STARS is voluntary and institutions may choose to skip any credits or categories.  However, since public reporting is important to the credibility of STARS, institutions will not earn points for credits if they do not provide the required information.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"Erroneous_Data\" target=\"_blank\"></a>If I believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I report it?<br /> </strong><span>Individuals with questions about a STARS report have the option to fill out a&nbsp;</span><a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/institutions/inquiry/\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Form</a>. <span>Questioners have the option to remain anonymous to the institution receiving the inquiry.&nbsp; A representative of the STARS Team will evaluate incoming accuracy inquiries and, assuming the questioner has provided sufficient information to merit further review, the STARS representative will work with the relevant STARS Liaison to respond to the question and communicate back with the questioner.&nbsp;</span>For more information, please review the complete <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/submission_review_policy_june_2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Submission Review Policy</a> approved by the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/3971/?root_category=about\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Steering Committee</a>&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">(policy currently under review)</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"Correct_Information\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How do I correct information in my institution\'s STARS Report after the information has been made public?</strong><br /> If an institution realizes it has made a mistake when documenting information in the STARS Reporting Tool after the information has been submitted for a STARS rating and is public on the STARS website, an individual assigned to the Administrator role within the Reporting Tool may correct this information by submitting a Data Corrections Request through the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report. The STARS Administrator will simply view the credit to be updated in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report on the STARS website and click on the pencil icon next to that credit. The icon will lead the STARS Administrator to the Data Corrections Request Form. &nbsp;Note that the Data Corrections Request form must be accessed through the institution\'s public report, not through the Reporting Tool. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Upon submitting this form, the STARS team will review the form to ensure the submitted information reflects a legitimate correction (as opposed to, for example, an update). Corrections will then be made to the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report. The corrected information in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will include a date stamp and note that explains the reason for the change and will be publicly available. The details of this process are explained in the  <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Correcting%20Mistakes%20in%20the%20Reporting%20Tool_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Policy for Correcting Mistakes in the Reporting Tool</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The process for making corrections to an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will be the same even if the change results in a new rating level. An institution may make corrections to its STARS Report with no charge up to a year after the STARS submission is received by AASHE. After that time, any institution-requested corrections require a  processing fee of $150 per correction. &nbsp;<span>If corrections are in response to a data accuracy inquiry originating from an external party or from an AASHE staff member, no processing fee shall be required.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"logo\" target=\"_blank\"></a>Can I use the STARS logo?</strong><br /> If you are interested in using the STARS logo, please email <a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">stars@aashe.org</a> and explain why you\'re  hoping to use the STARS logo and in what capacity.<span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"1.1\" target=\"_blank\"></a>Our institution is currently registered for STARS 1.0 or STARS 1.1 and we noticed that a new version of STARS (1.2) has been launched. How are we affected by the release of STARS 1.2?</strong><br /> Institutions that have been using <a href=\"/pages/about/history/stars-10.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.0 or STARS 1.1</a> may either continue reporting under this version of STARS or have the option to migrate their data into <a href=\"/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.2</a>. A button, which will actualize the migration, will be available in the Reporting Tool within the box at the top of the \"My Summary\" section. Institutions should note that not all of the reporting fields in STARS 1.0 and STARS 1.1 are the same as the reporting fields in STARS 1.2. This means that if an institution chooses to migrate its data from STARS 1.0 or STARS 1.1 into STARS 1.2, credits that were complete in the 1.0 or 1.1 version may require additional reporting to fulfill the requirements in the 1.2 version.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"subsequent\" target=\"_self\"></a>Are there any special considerations for institutions submitting subsequent reports?<br /></strong>Institutions submitting a subsequent report should be mindful of those areas within STARS that must be updated each time an institution submits for a new rating:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Time-frame - STARS reports should include an institution\'s most recent data available. &nbsp;Although migrating data from previous reports makes submitting a subsequent report more efficient, institutions should review each field and update information based on the most recent data available.</li>\r\n<li>Innovation credits - A criterion of the Innovation category in STARS states that \"an institution can only claim a particular activity as an innovation credit once.\" &nbsp;When re-submitting for a STARS rating, a previously-submitted innovation credit cannot be re-submitted.</li>\r\n<li>President\'s letter - A letter from an institution\'s president, chancellor, or highest ranking CEO affirming the accuracy of a STARS report is required for each STARS submission. &nbsp;Subsequent reports must include new letters of affirmation. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" class=\"mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 2105px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow: hidden;\">\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica; color: #333333; background: white;\">Institutions submitting a subsequent report should be mindful of those areas within a STARS report that must be updated each time an institution submits for a new rating:&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol; color: #333333;\">&middot;<span style=\"font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica; color: #333333; background: white;\">Timeframe &ndash; STARS reports should include an institution&rsquo;s most recent data available.&nbsp; Although migrating data from previous reports makes submitting a subsequent report more efficient, institutions should review each field and update information based on the most recent data available.&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol; color: #333333;\">&middot;<span style=\"font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica; color: #333333; background: white;\">President&rsquo;s letter &ndash; A letter from an institution&rsquo;s president, chancellor, or highest ranking CEO affirming the accuracy of a STARS report is required for each STARS submission.&nbsp; Subsequent reports must include new letters of affirmation from the highest ranking CEO.</span></p>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt; font-family: Aller; mso-fareast-font-family: Calibri; mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica; color: #333333; background: white; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Innovation credits &ndash; A criterion for the Innovation category in STARS states that &ldquo;An institution can only claim a particular activity as an innovation credit once. When re-submitting for a STARS rating, an innovation credit that the institution submitted previously cannot be re-submitted.&rdquo;</span></div>',1,'reporting-and-information-sharing','<p>How do I get started with STARS after I successfully register as a STARS Participant?<a href=\"#getting_started\" target=\"_self\"></a><br /> How can institutions demonstrate they have earned a credit?<br /> What timeframe should I use when reporting data for STARS?<br /> Will the STARS data be made public?<br /> What if institutions don\'t want to disclose certain information or make it publicly available (investment information, for example) or if an institution just wants to post one of the sections?<br /> If I believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I report it?<br /> How do I correct information in my institution&rsquo;s STARS Report after the information has been made public?<br /> Can I use the STARS logo?</p>',4104,'2013-06-14 10:53:47'),
	(108,'Ratings and Credits','2009-12-02 12:21:23',22,'<!--break-->\r\n<p><a href=\"#levels\" target=\"_self\">What are the STARS rating levels?</a><br /> <a href=\"#mean\" target=\"_self\">What does earning a STARS rating mean?</a><br /> <a href=\"#valid\" target=\"_self\">How long is a STARS rating valid? </a><br /> <a href=\"#get\" target=\"_self\">What will campuses get for earning a STARS rating?</a><br /> <a href=\"#often\" target=\"_self\">How often can an institution submit for a STARS rating? </a><br /> <a href=\"#third_party\" target=\"_self\">Is third-party verification required? </a><br /> <a href=\"#true\" target=\"_self\">How will the public know that the information reported from institutions is true?</a><br /> <a href=\"#Erroneous_Data\" target=\"_self\">If I believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I report it?</a><br /> <a href=\"#third_party\" target=\"_self\">How is innovation encouraged or rewarded?</a> <br /> <a href=\"#next_step\" target=\"_self\">Will STARS address the idea of getting campuses to take the \"next step&rdquo;?</a></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"levels\" target=\"_blank\"></a>What are the STARS rating levels?</strong><br />STARS Bronze - minimum score required: 25<br /> STARS Silver - minimum score required: 45<br /> STARS Gold - minimum score required: 65<br /> STARS Platinum - minimum score required: 85<br />STARS Reporter - no scores are made public</p>\r\n<p>An institution that wishes to participate in STARS but does not want to publish their score may participate as a STARS Reporter.  These institutions receive the same benefits as institutions that pursue a STARS rating, including positive recognition for participation and the ability to share data publicly.  After seeing their final score, all participants are able to choose STARS Reporter status before completing their final submission and making it public.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"mean\" target=\"_self\"></a>What does earning a STARS rating mean? </strong><br /> Each STARS rating is an indication of sustainability leadership.&nbsp; The STARS rating is earned by institutions that have registered for STARS and have gone through a comprehensive process of collecting and publicly reporting information related to their sustainability performance. STARS is a self-assessment and therefore AASHE does not certify or award ratings.&nbsp; STARS ratings are achieved by institutions that have successfully completed a STARS submission and have earned the score that corresponds to a particular <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/ratings-and-credits.html#levels\" target=\"_self\">STARS rating level</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"valid\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How long is a STARS rating valid? </strong><br /> A STARS rating is good for three years, however an institution may   submit for a new STARS rating as often as once per year.   An additional   registration fee is required each time an institution resubmits for a rating.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"get\" target=\"_blank\"></a>What will campuses get for earning a STARS rating?</strong><br /> Campuses will be able to use a STARS logo with their rating level on their website and print materials. (Terms of use for this logo will be distributed when the institution receives the rating).</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"often\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How often can an institution submit for a </strong><strong>STARS rating</strong><strong>? </strong><br />An institution that registers for STARS gains 12-months of continual  access to the STARS Reporting Tool. An institution may submit for a new  STARS rating as often as once during this 12-month period.  A STARS  Rating is valid for three years.&nbsp; After three years, an  institution  will need to resubmit a STARS Report to claim a valid rating.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"third_party\" target=\"_blank\"></a>Is third-party verification required? </strong><br /> At this time, third-party verification is not required nor does AASHE provide incentives for third-party verification.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"true\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How will the public know that the information reported from institutions is true? </strong><br /> STARS has built-in provisions to help ensure that information campuses submit is accurate.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>First, for each credit, a point person from the institution will provide a statement that the information submitted is accurate.</li>\r\n<li>Second, the institution&rsquo;s president or chancellor must write a <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/reporting-and-information-sharing.html#letter\" target=\"_self\">letter</a> stating that all the information submitted is true.</li>\r\n<li>Third, all information that the institution submits will be made publicly available through the STARS website.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><a name=\"Erroneous_Data\" target=\"_blank\"></a><strong>If I believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I report it?</strong><br /> Individuals with questions about one or more fields in a STARS report may fill out a <a href=\"/institutions/inquiry/\" target=\"_self\">&nbsp;STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Form</a>. A STARS staff member will evaluate the data accuracy inquiry and will follow-up as appropriate with the institution in question.&nbsp; Individuals have the option to remain anonymous to the institution receiving the inquiry.&nbsp; For more information, please review the complete&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/submission_review_policy_june_2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Submission Review Policy</a> approved by the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/3971/?root_category=about\" target=\"_self\">STARS Steering Committee</a>&nbsp;(policy currently under review).</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"innovation\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How is innovation encouraged or rewarded? </strong><br /> Like the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) green building rating system, STARS allocates points that reward innovative solutions to sustainability challenges. See the most <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">current version of STARS</a> for details associated with Innovation Credits.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"next_step\" target=\"_blank\"></a>Will STARS address the idea of getting campuses to take the \"next step&rdquo;?</strong><br /> STARS can be a starting point for institutions that are just beginning to address sustainability or it can be used as a vehicle for showcasing a leading institution&rsquo;s innovative sustainability strategies.  Since STARS includes ambitious, long-term sustainability achievements, all campuses will find something to strive for within the system.</p>',1,'ratings-and-credits','<p>What are the STARS Rating levels?<br /> What does earning a STARS Rating mean?<br /> How long is a STARS Rating valid?<br /> What will campuses get for earning a STARS Rating?<br /> How often can an institution submit for a STARS Rating?<br /> Is third-party verification required?<br /> How will the public know that the information reported from institutions is true?<br /> If I&nbsp;believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I&nbsp;report it?<br /> How is innovation encouraged or rewarded? <br /> Is third-party verification required?<br /> Will STARS address the idea of getting campuses to take the \"next step&rdquo;?</p>',4105,'2013-04-11 12:26:20'),
	(110,'Relationship to Other Systems','2009-12-02 12:23:39',23,'<!--break-->\r\n<p><a href=\"#other_systems\" target=\"_self\">What is the difference between STARS and other campus sustainability assessment systems?</a><br /> <a href=\"#working\" target=\"_self\">Is AASHE working with the other systems so campuses don\'t have to complete so many surveys?</a><br /> <a href=\"#acupcc\" target=\"_self\">How do STARS and the American College and University Presidents&rsquo; Climate Commitment (ACUPCC) complement each other?</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"#acupcc\" target=\"_self\"><strong></strong></a><strong><a name=\"other_systems\" target=\"_self\"></a>What is the difference between STARS and other campus sustainability assessment systems? </strong></p>\r\n<p>There are several key features that distinguish STARS from other campus sustainability rating systems, including the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Open development process</strong>&ndash;STARS is the result of a collaborative <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/history/\" target=\"_self\">development process</a> that involved hundreds of individuals and multiple public comment periods. Moving forward, AASHE will continue to engage stakeholders in higher education and sustainability, as well as the general public, to seek feedback on the system and ideas for improvements. </li>\r\n<li><strong>Fully transparent methodology</strong>&ndash;The criteria that determine a STARS rating are transparent and accessible to anyone.  This means you can see exactly how each participating institution received its score and what your institution needs to do to improve its score.</li>\r\n<li><strong>High-quality data</strong>&ndash;The <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a> provides detailed information about each credit to help ensure data comparability.  Further, the STARS Reporting Tool incorporates controls that limit the possibility of user error.  Moreover, STARS publishes submissions online and requires a &ldquo;responsible party&rdquo; to be associated with every credit.  By contrast, other rating systems gather much of their data through surveys that provide limited supporting information and require little to no supporting documentation.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Comprehensive approach</strong>&ndash;STARS awards points for a broader variety of sustainability activity than other rating systems.  Also, consistent with the original and long-standing meaning of sustainability, STARS includes credits related to an institution&rsquo;s social performance, while other systems tend to focus exclusively or primarily on environmental performance.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Absolute scale</strong>&ndash;STARS ratings are based on an absolute scale of progress toward sustainability and are not relative to the performance of other institutions.  There are a couple of benefits to this approach.  First, the scale stays relatively constant over time, thereby providing greater predictability in scoring over time and avoiding the problems associated with &ldquo;moving targets.&rdquo;  Second, the use of an absolute scale better encourages both cooperation among schools and continuous improvement toward sustainability since it keeps the focus on the end goal of sustainability rather than just on being better than other schools.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Community governance</strong>&ndash;STARS is the only campus sustainability rating system that is largely <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/\" target=\"_self\">governed by members of the campus sustainability community</a>.  Additionally, it is the only system with the support and involvement of a <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/3978/\" target=\"_self\">variety of higher education associations</a>.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Intended for institutions of all types</strong>&ndash;STARS is intended for all types of higher education institutions, from community colleges to research universities.  Other rating systems were designed for specific types of institutions and often exclude other types.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Only positive ratings</strong>&ndash;STARS provides only positive recognition; there are no bad grades.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Overall, while we respect the role other systems have played in raising the visibility of campus sustainability, we believe that STARS provides a substantially more meaningful assessment of an institution&rsquo;s sustainability performance than other systems available today.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"working\" target=\"_self\"></a>Is AASHE working with the other systems so campuses don\'t have to complete so many surveys? </strong><br /> Yes. Since March 2011, the Association for the Advancement of Sustainability  in Higher Education (AASHE), The Princeton Review, Sierra magazine, and  the Sustainable Endowments Institute has been collaborating on an effort  to streamline the reporting process for institutions that choose to  participate in various higher education sustainability assessments. The  intent of this initiative is to streamline the reporting process and  reduce the amount of time campus staff spend completing related surveys.</p>\r\n<p>The result of this collaboration is the creation of the <a href=\"/pages/get-involved/campus-sustainability-data-collector/campus-sustainability-data-collector.html\" target=\"_self\">Campus Sustainability Data Collector</a> hosted by AASHE. The Data Collector is modeled after the STARS Reporting Tool and is  available at no cost. However, this option does not include all of the <a href=\"/pages/get-involved/campus-sustainability-data-collector/data-collector-benefits.html\" target=\"_self\">benefits</a> of the STARS Reporting Tool or those associated with being a STARS Participant.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"acupcc\" target=\"_self\"></a>How do STARS and the American College and University Presidents&rsquo; Climate Commitment (ACUPCC) complement each other?</strong><br /> <a href=\"../../../../pages/about/\" target=\"_self\">STARS</a>&reg; is a transparent, self-reporting framework for colleges and universities to measure their comprehensive sustainability performance in all areas of the campus including Education &amp; Research, Operations, and Planning, Administration &amp; Engagement.&nbsp; Data from STARS Participants&rsquo; STARS Reports are available <a href=\"../../../../institutions/rated/\" target=\"_self\">publicly</a> allowing all Participants to share their sustainability practices and programs with the higher education community as well as benchmark their successes over time.&nbsp; The <a href=\"http://www.presidentsclimatecommitment.org/\" target=\"_self\">ACUPCC</a> is a pledge made by college and university presidents on behalf of their institutions, to pursue climate neutrality in campus operations, to promote the education, research and community engagement needed for the rest of society to do the same, and to hold themselves accountable by <a href=\"http://acupcc.aashe.org/\" target=\"_self\">publicly reporting</a> on their progress.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Activities that are required under the ACUPCC are rewarded with points in several STARS <a href=\"../../../../pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">credits</a>.&nbsp; For example, creating a climate action plan, conducting an inventory of greenhouse gas emissions, developing a climate neutrality plan, incorporating sustainability in the curriculum, and greenhouse gas reduction measures (such as providing public transportation options, and minimizing waste) are all actions that contribute to fulfilling the ACUPCC and will also earn an institution points in STARS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!-- @font-face {   font-family: \"?? ??\"; }@font-face {   font-family: \"Cambria Math\"; }@font-face {   font-family: \"Cambria\"; }p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal { margin: 0in 0in 0.0001pt; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria; }.MsoChpDefault { font-family: Cambria; }div.WordSection1 { page: WordSection1; } -->\r\n<p><!-- @font-face {   font-family: \"?? ??\"; }@font-face {   font-family: \"Cambria Math\"; }@font-face {   font-family: \"Cambria\"; }p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal { margin: 0in 0in 0.0001pt; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria; }.MsoChpDefault { font-family: Cambria; }div.WordSection1 { page: WordSection1; } --> AASHE, along with Second Nature and eco-America, was an original supporting organization of the ACUPCC&nbsp;and continues to be<span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;\"><span>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;\"> </span>a <a href=\"http://www.presidentsclimatecommitment.org/about/faqs#5\" target=\"_self\">supporting organization</a>. AASHE is also the organization that hosts and maintains STARS. Second Nature is the lead supporting organization of the ACUPCC and a <a href=\"../../../../pages/about/governance/stars-partner-organizations.html\" target=\"_self\">Founding Partner</a> of the STARS Program.</p>',1,'relationship-to-other-systems','<p>What is the difference between STARS and other campus sustainability assessment systems?<br /> Is AASHE working with the other systems so campuses don\'t have to complete so many surveys?<br /> How do STARS and the American College and University Presidents&rsquo; Climate Commitment (ACUPCC) complement each other?</p>',4107,'2012-07-11 08:41:03'),
	(0,'FAQs','2009-12-02 16:50:57',24,'<p>Have general questions about the overall STARS&nbsp;program, the history and development of STARS, participation in the program, reporting and information sharing, ratings and credits, or how STARS&nbsp;differs from other rating systems?&nbsp; Visit our <a href=\"http://stars.dev.aashe.org/pages/about/\">About</a> page for a complete listing of <a href=\"http://stars.dev.aashe.org/pages/faqs/?root_category=about\">FAQs</a> on STARS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',0,'faqs','<p>Have general questions about the overall STARS&nbsp;program, the history and development of STARS, participation in the program, reporting and information sharing, ratings and credits, or how STARS&nbsp;differs from other rating systems?&nbsp; Visit our <a href=\"http://stars.dev.aashe.org/pages/about/\">About</a> page for a complete listing of <a href=\"http://stars.dev.aashe.org/pages/faqs/?root',4111,'2010-12-08 21:01:50'),
	(0,'How do I estimate 2005 baseline data?','2009-12-15 11:40:47',25,'<p>STARS includes four credits (OP 5: Greenhouse Gas Emissions Reduction, OP 7: Building Energy Consumption, OP 17: Waste Reduction, and OP 22: Water Consumption) that are based on comparing performance to a 2005 baseline year.</p>\r\n<p>If an institution does not have 2005 data, it may either:</p>\r\n<p>a)	Estimate 2005 data using a trend line based on at least three years worth of data<br />\r\nb)	Estimate conservatively (i.e., estimate that performance has not changed between the baseline and performance year).  Following this approach, an institution would not be able to claim points during its first STARS submission, but would be able to use its previously estimated baseline for subsequent submissions.</p>\r\n<p>Some of the 2005 baseline figures are based on multiple components.  If an institution has data for some, but not all, of the components of the baseline figure, it may follow either of the approaches above to estimate the missing data and then combine it with the available data.</p>\r\n<p>For example, the baseline for OP 17: Waste Reduction is based on the sum of garbage, recycling, and compost tonnage.  If an institution had garbage data only for 2005, it could estimate recycling and compost weights and then add that to the garbage data to estimate the 2005 total.  <br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>',1,'how-do-i-estimate-2005-baseline-data','<p>STARS includes four credits (OP 5: Greenhouse Gas Emissions Reduction, OP 7: Building Energy Consumption, OP 17: Waste Reduction, and OP 22: Water Consumption) that are based on comparing performance to a 2005 baseline year.</p>\r\n<p>If an institution does not have 2005 data, it may either:</p>',4160,'2010-12-08 21:01:50'),
	(300,'Media Coverage','2010-01-05 14:31:56',26,'<!--break-->\r\n<p>Recent <a href=\"#national_press\" target=\"_self\">national press</a>, <a href=\"#campus_articles\" target=\"_self\">articles in campus newspapers and on campus websites</a>, <a href=\"#blog_posts\" target=\"_self\">blog posts</a>, <a href=\"#press_releases\" target=\"_self\">press releases</a>, and other media coverage of STARS are listed below. Have we missed something?&nbsp; Please email <a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_blank\">stars@aashe.org</a> to suggest a news item to add to the list. For articles published over a year ago, view the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/news-events/media-archive.html\" target=\"_self\">Media Archive</a>.</p>\r\n<h3><a name=\"national_press\" target=\"_self\"></a>Articles in National, Regional, and Local Press</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.pe.com/local-news/riverside-county/riverside/riverside-headlines-index/20130619-riverside-ucrs-sustainability-efforts-earn-honor.ece\" target=\"_self\">Riverside: UCR\'s sustainability efforts earn honor</a><br /><em>The Press-Enterprise&nbsp;</em>(Jun. 19, 2013)</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2013/05/31/3040660/uc-merced-connect-campus-green.html\" target=\"_self\">UC Merced Connect: Campus\' green efforts recognized</a><br /><em>Merced Sun-Star&nbsp;</em>(May 28, 2013)</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.swrnn.com/2013/05/25/uc-san-diego-receives-gold-rating-for-sustainability/\" target=\"_self\">UC San Diego receives \'gold rating\' for sustainability</a><br /><em>Southwest Riverside News Network&nbsp;</em>(May 25, 2013)</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.grbj.com/articles/76596-gvsus-commitment-to-sustainability-earns-it-top-national-honors\" target=\"_self\">GVSU\'s commitment to sustainability earns it top national honors</a><br /><em>Grand Rapids Business Journal&nbsp;</em>(Apr. 12, 2013)</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://surfky.com/index.php/communities/54-local-hopkinsville-top-news/29028-hcc-fir