	(300,'STARS Participant Benefits','2011-11-03 10:15:09',73,'<p>Once an institution registers for STARS, and the registration fee has been submitted to AASHE, the institution is recognized as a STARS Participant.&nbsp; STARS Participants receive 12-months of continuous access to the STARS Reporting Tool and are encouraged to submit their inaugural STARS Report during this time frame. Once a STARS Participant submits its STARS Report and earns a STARS rating, this rating is valid for three years.&nbsp; However, STARS Participants are encouraged to participate in STARS on an annual basis and have the opportunity to do so, at a discounted rate, so they can continue tracking their STARS data.</p>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"3\" cellpadding=\"10\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>STARS Fees</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>First-time Participants</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>Annual Participants</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>AASHE Member</td>\r\n<td>$900</td>\r\n<td>$450</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Non-member</td>\r\n<td>$1,400</td>\r\n<td>$700</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>Benefits</h2>\r\n<p>Benefits of becoming a STARS Participant include, but are not limited to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Access to the online <strong>STARS Reporting Tool</strong>, which includes:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -<strong> Data synchronization</strong> with other specific rating and ranking organizations<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - <strong>Automated point calculation</strong> for each STARS credit<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -<strong> PDF Exports</strong> of Submission Data<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - Ability to <strong>share data </strong>with other organizations outside of AASHE<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - <strong>Continuous access </strong>to update data<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - Option to give <strong>multiple users access</strong> to the STARS Report<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -<strong> Data tracking resources</strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -<strong> STARS seal</strong> <strong>logo</strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>- Email templates</strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - Template <strong>press release</strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - <strong>Promotional tools</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Earn a STARS rating and <strong>be recognized as a STARS rated institution</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Publicly posted STARS Report</strong> on the STARS website</li>\r\n<li>Full access to&nbsp;<strong>STARS Data Displays</strong></li>\r\n<li>Opportunities to <strong>influence STARS technical development</strong></li>\r\n<li>Inclusion in <strong>STARS Quarterly Review</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Free admission</strong> to STARS webinars</li>\r\n<li>And more!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>View a printable version of the STARS Participant <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/benefits_of_participating_in_stars_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">benefits</a> (pdf).</p>',0,'stars-participant-benefits','<p>Once an institution registers for STARS, and the registration fee has  been submitted to AASHE, the institution is recognized as a STARS  Participant.&nbsp; STARS Participants receive 12-months of continuous access  to the STARS Reporting Tool and are encouraged to submit their STARS  Report during this time frame. Once a STARS Participant submits its  STARS Report and earns a STARS rating, this rating is valid for three  years.&nbsp; However, STARS Participants are encouraged to participate in  STARS on an annual basis and have the opportunity to do so, at a  discounted rate, so they can continue tracking their STARS data.</p>',NULL,'2013-07-30 12:45:11'),
	(500,'Step-by-Step Through the STARS Process','2010-04-07 09:59:16',36,'<p>Interested in participating in STARS but unsure of what is involved?&nbsp; This step-by-step guide outlines the details of the STARS&nbsp;process from registration to submission.&nbsp; Find additional details about the STARS process in the \"<a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/help/getting-started/\" target=\"_self\">Help</a>\" section of the STARS website.</p>\r\n<p><strong>1)  Determine if STARS is Right for your Institution: </strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Review the STARS Credit Checklist (<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_credit_checklist.pdf\" target=\"_self\">pdf</a>) (<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_credit_checklist.xls\" target=\"_self\">Excel</a>) for an overview of the credits included in STARS</li>\r\n<li>Download a free copy of the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a> for full details about STARS</li>\r\n<li>Check out the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/4740/?root_category=get-involved\" target=\"_self\">benefits of participating</a></li>\r\n<li>Review the STARS <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/faqs/?root_category=about\" target=\"_self\">FAQs</a> or contact <a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">stars@aashe.org</a> if you have any questions</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>2) Register:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If you don&rsquo;t have one already, create an <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/accounts/help\" target=\"_self\">AASHE Account</a>.  Anyone may create an AASHE Account, and users must log in with their AASHE Account in order to <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/4269/?root_category=get-involved\" target=\"_self\">register</a> for STARS.</li>\r\n<li>Provide the name and contact information for the institution&rsquo;s STARS Liaison (the primary point of contact at the institution on STARS issues).</li>\r\n<li>Provide the name and contact information for one executive-level administrator (president, chancellor, vice president, vice chancellor, or provost) for AASHE to copy on the registration confirmation e-mail. Copying an administrator on the registration e-mail helps ensure that each institution&rsquo;s leadership is aware of its participation in STARS.</li>\r\n<li>Agree to the STARS Terms and Conditions of Use.</li>\r\n<li>Make a one-time payment that covers registration, access to the Reporting Tool for one year, and one submission.  Registrants may pay by credit card or check.</li>\r\n<li>Use the STARS Participant logo and template press release to publicize your institution&rsquo;s participation in the program.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>3) Report and Share Information:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Use your AASHE Account to log-in to the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">STARS website</a> and access the Reporting Tool.</li>\r\n<li>Grant others access to enter data so they can help with the reporting process.</li>\r\n<li>Specify the boundary for your institution&rsquo;s STARS submission.  The institutional boundary refers to the portions of the physical campus that are included.  Each institution is expected to include its entire main campus when reporting.  It may choose whether or not to include satellite campuses and other land holdings.</li>\r\n<li>Enter data and information that meets the specifications for each credit.  (The <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a> includes a list of reporting fields for each credit.)</li>\r\n<li>Affirm the accuracy of the information submitted by specifying a responsible party for each credit and providing his or her contact information.</li>\r\n<li>STARS Participants also have the      option of sharing their data with The Princeton Review, Sierra magazine,      and/or the Sustainable Endowments Institute. These organizations are      interested in institutions completing as much of STARS as possible, in      addition to the supplemental section. The supplement section includes      additional fields, outside of the STARS reporting fields that hold no      weight on a STARS rating.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>4)  Submit for a Rating:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Double-check all of the saved information to make sure it&rsquo;s accurate.</li>\r\n<li>Upload a letter from the president or chancellor that affirms the accuracy of the submission.</li>\r\n<li>Determine if you want to submit as a Reporter.</li>\r\n<li>Submit all information. All data and credit information will be publicly posted on the STARS website upon submission.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>5)  Spread the Word:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Highlight your achievements by using the STARS rating logo and issuing a press release.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/4269/?root_category=get-involved\" target=\"_self\">Renew</a> your      institutions participation with STARS.&nbsp;      Institutions that renew within 90 days of their access to the STARS      Reporting Tool expiring are eligible for a 50% discount (i.e. $450 for      AASHE members and $700 for non-members instead of $900 for AASHE members      and $1,400 for non-members).&nbsp; </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>6) Repeat the Process:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>&nbsp;A STARS rating is valid for three years, but an institution may choose to submit its data as often as once per 12-month subscription with STARS.&nbsp; Remember that updates to your information are only made public when you submit your data.</li>\r\n</ul>',0,'step-by-step-through-the-stars-process','<p>Interested in participating in STARS but unsure of what is involved?&nbsp; This step-by-step guide outlines the details of the STARS&nbsp;process from registration to submission.</p>\r\n<p><strong>1)  Determine if STARS is Right for your Institution: </strong></p>',5053,'2013-07-30 09:43:52'),
	(200,'How-To-Videos','2010-05-10 15:30:29',38,'<p>AASHE&nbsp;has created a series of How-To-Videos to help get you started with the STARS&nbsp;program.&nbsp; The videos are approximately three minutes in length and provide detailed information about specific features of the STARS&nbsp;Reporting Tool.&nbsp; Additional videos will be posted to this page as they become available.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/user/aasheorg#p/c/F7621E4D0FDFD248/0/T1MdqRTagrI\" target=\"_self\">Logging into the STARS&nbsp;Reporting Tool</a> (3:23)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/user/aasheorg#p/c/F7621E4D0FDFD248/2/oPpwCQjEIEU\" target=\"_self\">Adding \"Users\" to a STARS&nbsp;Report</a> (3:35)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Have suggestions for additional How-To-Video topics?&nbsp; Contact us!&nbsp; <a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">stars@aashe.org</a></p>',0,'how-to-videos','<p>AASHE&nbsp;has created a series of How-To-Videos to help get you started with the STARS&nbsp;program.&nbsp; The videos are approximately three minutes in length and provide detailed information about specific features of the STARS&nbsp;Reporting Tool.&nbsp; Additional videos will be posted to this page as they become available.</p>',5322,'2012-07-05 10:58:07'),
	(0,'STARS Policies','2010-09-28 16:53:18',43,'<p>As AASHE has received comments, suggestions, and questions from STARS participants and unique circumstances have come to light, there has been a need to develop policies to address various issues in STARS.  Policies that directly affect STARS participants are provided below.</p>\r\n<h2>STARS Eligibility Policy</h2>\r\n<p>Any college or university in the United States or Canada may participate in STARS. An institution is defined by having a separate and distinct administration (e.g. president or chancellor). For institutions that may be a part of a larger system, they must have an administration that is separate and distinct from others in the system of which it is a part. The complete <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Eligibility%20Requirements%20Proposal%20for%20SC.%208.19.pdf\">Eligibility Requirements for STARS Policy</a> is available on the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/3971/?root_category=about\">STARS Steering Committee webpage</a>.</p>\r\n<p>If an institution or entity does not meet these requirements but you believe there is a compelling case for the participation of that institution or entity in STARS, please complete the<span> <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/cfm/eligibility-enquiry/\">Eligibility Enquiry Form</a>.</span> This information will be evaluated by the STARS staff, who will decide if the institution or entity is eligible to participate in STARS.</p>\r\n<h2>Correcting Mistakes in a STARS Submission Policy</h2>\r\n<p>If an institution realizes it has made a mistake when documenting information in the STARS Reporting Tool, after the information has been submitted for a STARS Rating and is public on the STARS website, the STARS Liaison may correct this information by completing a <strong><span>STARS Data Change Request Form (LINK).</span></strong>  This form, available in the STARS Reporting Tool, will then be submitted to the STARS team for review prior to the information being corrected in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report. The corrected information in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will include a date stamp and note that explains the reason for the change and will be publicly available.  The details of this process are explained in the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Correcting%20Mistakes%20in%20the%20Reporting%20Tool_0.pdf\">Correcting Mistakes in the Reporting Tool Policy.</a></p>\r\n<p>The process for making corrections to an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will be the same even if the change results in a new rating level. An institution may make corrections to its STARS Report with no charge up to a year after the STARS submission is received by AASHE. After that time, any institution-requested corrections require a small processing fee of $150 per correction.</p>\r\n<h2>STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Policy</h2>\r\n<p>The information in an institution\'s STARS Report is self-reported and is not verified by AASHE or a third party. The <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/institutions/inquiry/\">STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Form</a> is available for individuals who wish to report erroneous data they have discovered within an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report.  Once the form has been completed and submitted, the individual&rsquo;s comments will be sent directly to the STARS Liaison of the institution in question. In accordance with the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Submission Review Proposal.pdf\">STARS Submission Review Policy</a>, the STARS Team encourages the individual with a concern and the STARS Liaison of the institution in question to resolve the issue. If direct communication between these two parties does not resolve the issue, a STARS staff member will evaluate the STARS submission accuracy inquiry and guide them through the next steps in the process.</p>\r\n<h2>STARS Technical Development Policy</h2>\r\n<p>Because STARS seeks continuous improvement, while balancing the needs of our users, our Steering Committee has adopted a <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Technical Development Proposal.pdf\">Technical Development Policy</a> to guide how new information will be incorporated into STARS.  Administrative changes will be made no more than quarterly; minor substantive changes will be made no more often than annually; and major revisions will be made no more often than bi-annually. <br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>',0,'stars-policies','<p>As AASHE has received comments, suggestions, and questions from STARS participants and unique circumstances have come to light, there has been a need to develop policies to address various issues in STARS.  Policies that directly affect STARS participants are provided below.</p>',10669,'2010-12-08 21:01:50'),
	(200,'STARS Policies','2010-10-05 12:18:00',45,'<p>As AASHE has received feedback from STARS participants and unique circumstances have come to light, the STARS Team has worked with the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/3971/?root_category=about\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Steering Committee</a> to develop policies to address various issues.  In general, policy development involves three steps.  First, the STARS Team considers an issue that has been raised.  Then, the STARS Team proposes an approach or several approaches to address the issue, which the STARS Steering Committee reviews.  Finally, if the Steering Committee approves a proposed approach, it becomes a policy.  Policies which directly affect STARS Participants are below.</p>\r\n<h2>STARS Eligibility Policy</h2>\r\n<p>Any college or university in the United States or Canada may participate in STARS. International institutions are welcome to participate in the <a href=\"../../../../pages/get-involved/stars-international-pilot.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS International Pilot</a>. An institution is defined by having a separate and distinct administration (e.g. president or chancellor). For an institution which may be a part of a larger system, it must have an administration that is separate and distinct from others in the system of which it is a part. The complete <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Eligibility Requirements Proposal for SC. 8.19.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Eligibility Requirements for STARS Policy</a> is available on the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/3971/?root_category=about\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Steering Committee webpage</a>.</p>\r\n<p>If an institution or entity does not meet these requirements, but you believe there is a compelling case for the participation of that institution or entity in STARS, please complete the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/cfm/eligibility-inquiry/\" target=\"_blank\">Eligibility Inquiry Form</a>. This information will be evaluated by the STARS staff, who will decide if the institution or entity is eligible to participate in STARS.</p>\r\n<h2>Policy for Correcting Mistakes in a STARS Report</h2>\r\n<p>If an institution realizes it has made a mistake when documenting information in the STARS Reporting Tool after the information has been submitted for a STARS Rating and is public on the STARS website, an individual designated as an Administrator within the Reporting Tool may correct this information by submitting a Data Corrections Request through the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report.  The STARS Administrator will simply view the credit to be updated in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report on the STARS website and click on the icon (<img src=\"http://stars.aashe.org/media/static/images/note_edit.png\" border=\"0\" align=\"bottom\" />) next to that credit.  The icon will lead the STARS Administrator to the Data Corrections Request Form.</p>\r\n<p>Upon submitting this form, the STARS Team will review the form to ensure the submitted information reflects a legitimate correction (as opposed to, for example, an update). Corrections will then be made to the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report. The corrected information in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will include a date stamp and note that explains the reason for the change and will be publicly available. The details of this process are explained in the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Correcting Mistakes in the Reporting Tool_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Policy for Correcting Mistakes in the Reporting Tool</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The process for making corrections to an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will be the same even if the change results in a new rating level. An institution may make corrections to its STARS Report with no charge up to a year after the STARS submission is received by AASHE. After that time, any institution-requested corrections require a&nbsp; processing fee of $150 per correction.</p>\r\n<h2>STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Policy</h2>\r\n<p>The information in an institution\'s STARS Report is self-reported and is not verified by AASHE or a third party. The <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/institutions/inquiry/\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Form</a> is available for individuals who wish to report erroneous data they have discovered within an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report. <span>Once the form has been completed and submitted, the individual&rsquo;s comments will be sent directly to the STARS Liaison assigned to that institution as well as to the STARS team.&nbsp; In submitting a STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry, </span><span>the questioner has the option to remain anonymous to the institution.&nbsp; </span><span>A representative of the STARS Team<span> </span></span><span>will follow up with the institution to determine if a data correction is needed.&nbsp; For more information, please review the</span>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/submission_review_policy_june_2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Submission Review Policy</a>, approved by the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/governance/steering-committee.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Steering Committee</a>&nbsp;(policy currently under review).</p>\r\n<h2><a name=\"Technical_Development\" target=\"_self\"></a>STARS Technical Development Policy</h2>\r\n<p>Because STARS seeks continuous improvement, while balancing the needs of our users, our Steering Committee has adopted a <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/technical_development_policy.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Technical Development Policy</a> to guide how new information will be incorporated into STARS.  Administrative changes will be made no more than quarterly; minor substantive changes will be made no more often than annually; and major revisions will be made no more often than bi-annually.</p>\r\n<h2>Discount for Renewing Participants</h2>\r\n<p>STARS Participants that registered   prior to January 1, 2011 will be    prompted to renew their registration at a 50% discount (i.e. $450 for    AASHE members and $700 for non-members) after submitting for a  rating.</p>\r\n<p>Institutions that   register after January 1, 2011 will be able   to  renew their participation with STARS at a 50% discount once their  12-months of access to the STARS Reporting Tool expires.</p>\r\n<h2>Access to the STARS Reporting Tool</h2>\r\n<p>All registrants, both new and renewing, will have 12 months of    continuous access to the Reporting Tool. During this 12-month cycle,   institutions may submit a STARS  Report at any time. If an institution   submits before the 12th month, it will still  have access to the   Reporting Tool until the end of its cycle. With this  benefit of   continual access, no extensions will be given. Ongoing  access to the   STARS Reporting Tool will allow your institution to  maintain accurate   data even after a STARS Rating is achieved.<span> <br /></span></p>',0,'stars-policies','',10722,'2013-08-08 15:49:05'),
	(0,'STARS Policies','2010-10-05 12:41:47',46,'<p>As AASHE has received comments, suggestions, and questions from STARS participants and unique circumstances have come to light, there has been a need to develop policies to address various issues in STARS.  Policies that directly affect STARS participants are provided below.</p>',0,'stars-policies','<p>As AASHE has received comments, suggestions, and questions from STARS participants and unique circumstances have come to light, there has been a need to develop policies to address various issues in STARS.  Policies that directly affect STARS participants are provided below.</p>',10723,'2010-12-08 21:01:50'),
	(200,'STARS Policies','2010-10-05 12:45:19',47,'<p>As AASHE has received comments, suggestions, and questions from STARS participants and unique circumstances have come to light, there has been a need to develop policies to address various issues in STARS.  Policies that directly affect STARS participants are provided below.</p>',0,'stars-policies','<p>As AASHE has received comments, suggestions, and questions from STARS participants and unique circumstances have come to light, there has been a need to develop policies to address various issues in STARS.  Policies that directly affect STARS participants are provided below.</p>',10724,'2010-12-08 21:01:50'),
	(200,'Recognition & Scoring','2010-10-26 14:08:54',48,'<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS only gives positive recognition - each level of recognition represents significant sustainability leadership. Participating in STARS, which includes gathering extensive data and sharing it publicly, represents a commitment to sustainability that should be applauded. </span></p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Levels of Recognition</h3>\r\n<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>There are four STARS ratings available (Bronze, Silver, Gold and Platinum). The table below summarizes the scoring thresholds corresponding with each rating.</span></p>\r\n<table border=\"1\">\r\n<colgroup><col width=\"241\"></col><col width=\"206\"></col></colgroup> \r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rating</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Minimum Score Required</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS Bronze</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>25</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS Silver</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>45</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS Gold</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>65</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS Platinum</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>85</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>STARS Reporter</strong><br /> In addition, any institution that wishes to participate in STARS but does not want to pursue an overall STARS rating or make their scores public may participate as a STARS Reporter. STARS Reporters receive many of the same benefits as institutions that pursue a STARS rating, including positive recognition for participation and the ability to share data publicly. All participants have the option to choose STARS Reporter status before completing their final submission and making it public.</p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">STARS Categories</h3>\r\n<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>An institution&rsquo;s STARS score is based on the percentage of applicable points it earns across four categories:</span><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">Academics (AC)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">Engagement (EN)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">Operations (OP)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">Planning &amp; Administration (PA)</span></li>\r\n</ol> <ol> </ol>\r\n<p><span>For example, if an institution earned 30 percent of all applicable points, the institution&rsquo;s overall score would be 30, making it eligible for a STARS Bronze Rating.</span></p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>Innovation</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>In addition to the credits in the four categories outlined above, institutions may earn up to 4 innovation credits for new and path-breaking practices and performances that are not covered by other STARS credits or that exceed the highest criterion of a current STARS credit. Innovation credits are not required to be specific to any category and are scored separately. Each earned innovation credit increases an institution&rsquo;s overall score by 1 point.</span></p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>Applicability</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Some credits do not apply to all institutions. For example, the credits about dining services do not apply to institutions that do not have dining services operations. Institutions will earn a score based on the percentage of applicable points they earn. In other words, credits that do not apply to an institution will not be counted against that &nbsp;institution&rsquo;s overall score.</span></p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>Variability</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>In addition, the number of points that are available for a credit may vary based on an institution&rsquo;s context. This variability is linked to third-party reference standards or methodologies for evaluating the sustainability impact of the area being evaluated in the credit. STARS 2.0 introduces this approach to contextual variability in the following&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">credits:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">OP 11: Biodiversity</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">OP 26: Water Use</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Timing</h3>\r\n<p><span><span>A STARS rating is in effect for three years. An institution may submit for a recognition&nbsp;</span><span>as often as once during each 12-month subscription period.&nbsp;<span><span>An institution without a valid subscription may submit as a Reporter. All participants have continuous access to the STARS Reporting Tool and may update information at any time<span><span>; however, the data which is shared publicly will only be updated when the institution </span><span>formally </span><span>submits </span><span>a new report.</span><span> </span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><em>While AASHE has strived for a fair and consistent approach to allocating points and ratings, this is an inherently subjective exercise. Developing a more robust point allocation methodology, including expanding the application of contextual variability as feasible, and finding additional ways to accommodate how regional variations and difference in institution type influence each institution&rsquo;s sustainability impacts, will be considered for future versions of STARS.</em></p>',1,'recognition-scoring','',10932,'2013-08-26 12:29:54'),
	(300,'Rating Levels','2010-10-26 14:09:57',49,'<p>Only positive ratings are available through STARS. Each rating level  represents significant sustainability leadership.  Participating in  STARS, which includes gathering extensive data and sharing it publicly,  represents a commitment to sustainability that should be applauded.</p>\r\n<p>There are two methods for earning a STARS rating. Institutions that  wish to participate in STARS but do not want to publish their scores may  participate as a STARS Reporter. Institutions that wish to be scored  may earn one of four other levels of STARS ratings: Bronze, Silver,  Gold, and Platinum.</p>\r\n<p>The following table summarizes the scoring thresholds corresponding with each Rating level.</p>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" width=\"500\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"center\"><strong>Rating<br /> </strong></td>\r\n<td align=\"center\"><strong>Minimum Score Required</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/rating.html#reporter\" target=\"_self\">STARS Reporter</a></td>\r\n<td align=\"center\">No scores are made public</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>STARS Bronze</td>\r\n<td align=\"center\">25</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>STARS Silver</td>\r\n<td align=\"center\">45</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>STARS Gold</td>\r\n<td align=\"center\">65</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>STARS Platinum</td>\r\n<td align=\"center\">85</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>Timeframe for Ratings</h2>\r\n<p>A STARS rating is in effect for three years.  An institution can submit for a Rating anytime during the 12 months it has access to the Reporting Tool.&nbsp; It is possible for the institution to update information in its profile throughout the 12 months of access; however, the data which is shared publicly will only be updated when the institution submits for a new rating. For more information, please see the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/governance/stars-policies.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Policy Page</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Once an institution has earned a credit, it is expected that the institution will make a good faith effort to maintain the status that made them eligible for the credit for the duration of the STARS rating.  While year-to-year fluctuations in some performance areas are to be expected, an institution would not qualify for a credit if it ended the practice or policy upon earning the credit and resumed the practice or policy when it was time to re-submit information.</p>\r\n<h2><a name=\"Reporter_Status\" target=\"_self\"></a><a name=\"Reporter_Status\" target=\"_self\"></a><a name=\"reporter\" target=\"_self\"></a>STARS Reporter Status</h2>\r\n<p>Any institution that wishes to participate in STARS but does not want   to publish their scores may participate as a STARS Reporter.  STARS   Reporter institutions receive the same benefits as institutions that   pursue a STARS rating, including positive recognition for participation   and the ability to share data publicly. However, the scores for   STARS&nbsp;Reporters will not be visible in their public report. After seeing   their final scores, all participants are able to choose STARS Reporter   status before completing their final submission and making it public.</p>\r\n<!--break-->\r\n<p><a href=\"#levels\" target=\"_self\">What are the STARS rating levels?</a><br /> <a href=\"#mean\" target=\"_self\">What does earning a STARS rating mean?</a><br /> <a href=\"#valid\" target=\"_self\">How long is a STARS rating valid? </a><br /> <a href=\"#get\" target=\"_self\">What will campuses get for earning a STARS rating?</a><br /> <a href=\"#often\" target=\"_self\">How often can an institution submit for a STARS rating? </a><br /> <a href=\"#third_party\" target=\"_self\">Is third-party verification required? </a><br /> <a href=\"#true\" target=\"_self\">How will the public know that the information reported from institutions is true?</a><br /> <a href=\"#Erroneous_Data\" target=\"_self\">If I believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I report it?</a><br /> <a href=\"#third_party\" target=\"_self\">How is innovation encouraged or rewarded?</a> <br /> <a href=\"#next_step\" target=\"_self\">Will STARS address the idea of getting campuses to take the \"next step&rdquo;?</a></p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"levels\" target=\"_blank\"></a>What are the STARS rating levels?</strong><br />STARS Bronze - minimum score required: 25<br /> STARS Silver - minimum score required: 45<br /> STARS Gold - minimum score required: 65<br /> STARS Platinum - minimum score required: 85<br />STARS Reporter - no scores are made public</p>\r\n<p>An institution that wishes to participate in STARS but does not want to publish their score may participate as a STARS Reporter.  These institutions receive the same benefits as institutions that pursue a STARS rating, including positive recognition for participation and the ability to share data publicly.  After seeing their final score, all participants are able to choose STARS Reporter status before completing their final submission and making it public.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"mean\" target=\"_self\"></a>What does earning a STARS rating mean? </strong><br /> Each STARS rating is an indication of sustainability leadership.&nbsp; The STARS rating is earned by institutions that have registered for STARS and have gone through a comprehensive process of collecting and publicly reporting information related to their sustainability performance. STARS is a self-assessment and therefore AASHE does not certify or award ratings.&nbsp; STARS ratings are achieved by institutions that have successfully completed a STARS submission and have earned the score that corresponds to a particular <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/ratings-and-credits.html#levels\" target=\"_self\">STARS rating level</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"valid\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How long is a STARS rating valid? </strong><br /> A STARS rating is good for three years, however an institution may   submit for a new STARS rating as often as once per year.   An additional   registration fee is required each time an institution resubmits for a rating.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"get\" target=\"_blank\"></a>What will campuses get for earning a STARS rating?</strong><br /> Campuses will be able to use a STARS logo with their rating level on their website and print materials. (Terms of use for this logo will be distributed when the institution receives the rating).</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"often\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How often can an institution submit for a </strong><strong>STARS rating</strong><strong>? </strong><br />An institution that registers for STARS gains 12-months of continual  access to the STARS Reporting Tool. An institution may submit for a new  STARS rating as often as once during this 12-month period.  A STARS  Rating is valid for three years.&nbsp; After three years, an  institution  will need to resubmit a STARS Report to claim a valid rating.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"third_party\" target=\"_blank\"></a>Is third-party verification required? </strong><br /> At this time, third-party verification is not required nor does AASHE provide incentives for third-party verification.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"true\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How will the public know that the information reported from institutions is true? </strong><br /> STARS has built-in provisions to help ensure that information campuses submit is accurate.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>First, for each credit, a point person from the institution will provide a statement that the information submitted is accurate.</li>\r\n<li>Second, the institution&rsquo;s president or chancellor must write a <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/reporting-and-information-sharing.html#letter\" target=\"_self\">letter</a> stating that all the information submitted is true.</li>\r\n<li>Third, all information that the institution submits will be made publicly available through the STARS website.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><a name=\"Erroneous_Data\" target=\"_blank\"></a><strong>If I believe there is erroneous data in an institution\'s STARS Report, how do I report it?</strong><br /> Individuals with questions about one or more fields in a STARS report may fill out a <a href=\"/institutions/inquiry/\" target=\"_self\">&nbsp;STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Form</a>. A STARS staff member will evaluate the data accuracy inquiry and will follow-up as appropriate with the institution in question.&nbsp; Individuals have the option to remain anonymous to the institution receiving the inquiry.&nbsp; For more information, please review the complete&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/submission_review_policy_june_2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Submission Review Policy</a> approved by the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/governance/3971/?root_category=about\" target=\"_self\">STARS Steering Committee</a>&nbsp;(policy currently under review).</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"innovation\" target=\"_blank\"></a>How is innovation encouraged or rewarded? </strong><br /> Like the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) green building rating system, STARS allocates points that reward innovative solutions to sustainability challenges. See the most <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">current version of STARS</a> for details associated with Innovation Credits.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a name=\"next_step\" target=\"_blank\"></a>Will STARS address the idea of getting campuses to take the \"next step&rdquo;?</strong><br /> STARS can be a starting point for institutions that are just beginning to address sustainability or it can be used as a vehicle for showcasing a leading institution&rsquo;s innovative sustainability strategies.  Since STARS includes ambitious, long-term sustainability achievements, all campuses will find something to strive for within the system.</p>',0,'rating','',10933,'2013-08-09 13:08:16'),
	(50,'Reporting','2010-11-02 10:23:32',54,'<p>All STARS&nbsp;reporting will be done using the online <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/tool/\" target=\"_self\">Reporting Tool</a>, which is only available to current STARS Participants. The <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a> is publicly available and provides the information necessary to gather the data required for STARS.  The descriptions of the STARS&nbsp;credits in the Technical Manual include the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Credit Rationale</strong>&ndash;provides background on the importance of the credit in the context of sustainability.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Criteria</strong>&ndash;describes how an institution earns points for the credit.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Applicability</strong>&ndash;indicates which institutions&rsquo; STARS Ratings will be affected by their responses to the credit. Some credits do not apply to some types of institutions. For example, credits involving residence halls do not apply to institutions that do not have residence halls.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Scoring</strong>&ndash;explains how points are allocated for the credit.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Reporting Fields</strong>&ndash;lists the fields that appear within the Reporting Tool for each credit. Some fields are required while others are listed as optional if the institution wishes to provide additional information.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Timeframe</strong>&ndash;describes the time period from which data should be drawn. For some credits, particularly those that are based on the presence of a policy or program, institutions should report on current practices (i.e. status at the time of reporting). Other credits, particularly those based on quantitative performance, require historical performance data, typically drawn from a one-year period.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Sampling and Data Standards</strong>&ndash;provides guidelines on when institutions may use a representative sample to measure performance and when samples are prohibited.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Additionally, a <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/5053/?root_category=get-involved\" target=\"_self\">step-by-step guide</a> to the details of the entire STARS process, from registration to submission, is also provided within the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/\" target=\"_self\">STARS website</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Institutional Boundary</h2>\r\n<p>Each institution is expected to include its entire main campus when  collecting data. Institutions may choose to include any other land  holdings, facilities, farms, and satellite campuses, as long as the  selected boundary is the same for every credit. Institutions will specify  the boundary for included data in the institutional information section  of the Reporting Tool. If an institution finds it necessary to exclude a  particular unit from its submission, the reason for excluding it must  be provided in the notes accompanying the submitted data.</p>\r\n<h2>Supplemental Data</h2>\r\n<p>STARS Participants reporting under STARS 1.2, or future versions of STARS, will be able to share the information documented for each STARS credit in the STARS Reporting Tool with the Princeton Review and Sierra magazine, if they choose to do so. In addition, there are some data points, not included in STARS, which these organizations are also interested in, that AASHE has identified as supplemental data in the reporting process. Any information documented in the supplemental section does not impact a STARS rating and will not be posted publicly in an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report. Completing these fields is optional but important if your institution would like to be included in Princeton Review Green Rating and/or American&rsquo;s Coolest Schools.</p>\r\n<p>Once your institution has completed documenting its data in the STARS Reporting Tool, it will have the option to allow other organizations to have access to this information for use in their publications. To allow access, STARS Participants much indicate which organization data will be shared with and save a snapshot of data to be shared.&nbsp; Instructions for taking and sharing snapshots of data are outlined in the &ldquo;Share Data&rdquo; tab in the &ldquo;My Summary&rdquo; section of the STARS Reporting Tool. Though all STARS information becomes public, sharing your institution&rsquo;s data in this manner allows these organizations to gain access to the data in a user-friendly manner that is easy to analyze. Please note, the Princeton Review and Sierra magazine may not use all of the data shared.</p>\r\n<p>Your institution must take a snapshot of its data and share this  information to be  considered for another organizations\' publications.  Instructions for  taking and sharing snapshots of data are outlined in  the \"Share Data\"  tab of the \"My Summary\" section in the STARS Reporting  Tool.</p>\r\n<h2>Submission Process</h2>\r\n<p>Once an institution has completed documenting all of the required data in the STARS Reporting Tool it may submit this data for a STARS Rating. The process for&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=De-t9F7GhnU\" target=\"_self\">finalizing a STARS submission</a> involves three steps.</p>\r\n<p><em>Step 1: </em>The institution will have the opportunity to edit the institutional boundary that was designated when the institution first started the STARS process. In addition, the institution will be able to see all of the credits in the STARS Reporting Tool that were left blank or marked as \"in progress\" and determine if any last minute changes need to be made to these credits.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Step 2: </em>At this time the institution will upload the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/reporting-and-information-sharing.html#letter\" target=\"_self\">President\'s Letter</a> which states that all of the information in the STARS submission is accurate and up-to-date.&nbsp; This letter may also serve as a cover letter to the institution\'s STARS Report.&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Please note that since acquiring a letter from the president may  take some time, AASHE encourages institutions to begin work with the  president\'s office several months prior to the submission deadline. </strong><strong> </strong>Also, the institution may choose if it would like to submit its STARS data as a <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/faqs/ratings-and-credits.html#levels\" target=\"_self\">STARS Reporter</a> or under the provisional rating it has achieved (STARS Bronze, Silver, Gold, or Platinum). Institutions that have earned less than 24 points will automatically achieve the STARS Reporter rating.</p>\r\n<p><em>Step 3: </em>The institution will confirm that the information documented in the STARS Reporting Tool is ready to be submitted for a STARS rating.</p>\r\n<p>Please note, once information is submitted for a STARS rating the institution\'s <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/institutions/rated/\" target=\"_self\">STARS Report</a> will be publicly available on the STARS website. Also, at this time, the institution may not add any additional information to its public STARS Report.&nbsp; However, a <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/governance/stars-policies.html\" target=\"_self\">Data Correction Request</a> may be submitted if an institution realizes it has made a mistake when documenting  information in the STARS Reporting Tool after the information has been  submitted for a STARS Rating and is public on the STARS website.</p>',0,'reporting','<p>All STARS&nbsp;reporting will be done using the online <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/tool/\" target=\"_self\">Reporting Tool</a>, which is only available to current STARS Participants. The <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/3993/?root_category=about\" target=\"_self\">STARS Technical Manual</a> is publicly available and provides the information necessary to gather the data required for STARS.</p>',10993,'2013-07-30 12:56:04'),
	(200,'Data Accuracy','2010-11-02 15:00:19',55,'<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">STARS data accuracy processes help to protect the credibility of STARS and provide a fair and transparent means for resolving questions about the accuracy of STARS data. Approved in July 2013, the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_data_accuracy_policy_07.19.13_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Data Accuracy Policy</a> explains the mechanisms AASHE uses to improve the accuracy of STARS data, including how concerns about the integrity of data are addressed.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Update</strong>: New data accuracy measures approved in 2013 include: (1) pre-publication and post-publication review of STARS reports by AASHE staff, and (2) flagging pending data accuracy inquiries in public STARS reports. Read more about these and other data accuracy measures in the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_data_accuracy_policy_07.19.13_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Data Accuracy Policy</a>.</p>\r\n<h3>Mechanisms for Report Accuracy</h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>For each credit, a </span><strong>Responsible Party </strong><span>from the institution provides a statement that the information submitted is accurate. The name of each Responsible Party is listed under each credit in the public STARS Report.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Each submitted report must be accompanied by a </span><strong>letter from the institution&rsquo;s president, chancellor, or highest ranking executive</strong><span> that affirms the accuracy of the institution&rsquo;s STARS report. Sign-off from the institution&rsquo;s chief executive promotes accuracy and encourages administrative involvement in STARS.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>All institutions wishing to pursue a Platinum rating will be subject to </span><strong>pre-publication review </strong><span>by AASHE staff. Staff may conduct random pre-publication review for other STARS reports.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>AASHE staff conduct </span><strong>post-publication review</strong><span> for all STARS reports after a rating has been earned.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>All </span><strong>information in STARS reports is made publicly available</strong><span> on the STARS website. If an individual or organization believes that erroneous data have been submitted, the</span><a href=\"/institutions/inquiry/\" target=\"_self\"><span> </span><span>STARS Data Accuracy Inquiry Form</span></a><span> </span><span>will bring the potential error to the attention of the STARS Liaison at that institution. &nbsp;Individuals submitting inquiries have the option to remain anonymous to the institution receiving the inquiry.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Each institution may submit a </span><strong>data correction request </strong><span>to correct mistakes in its STARS report after a rating has been earned and the report has been made public on the STARS website. Individuals at the institution with Administrator access within the Reporting Tool may submit correction requests. The process for making corrections remains the same even if the change results in a new STARS rating level.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>For more information on STARS data accuracy, please review the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_data_accuracy_policy_07.19.13_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Data Accuracy Policy</a>.</p>',1,'stars-report-accuracy','',11014,'2013-08-23 10:06:23'),
	(100,'Technical Manual','2011-02-08 13:42:25',61,'<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_2.0_technical_manual_cover.png\" border=\"0\" width=\"180\" height=\"255\" style=\"float: left; border: 1px solid black;\" /></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS 2.0 is the current version of STARS. &nbsp;The STARS 2.0 Technical Manual (pdf) is the go-to guide for the STARS credits and is organized into four main categories (Academics, Engagement, Operations, and Planning &amp; Administration), which are broken down into sub-categories where the individual STARS credits are located. &nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Credit Outline</h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Each STARS credit in the Technical Manual includes the following details:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Credit Rationale</strong>&ndash;provides background on the importance of the credit in the context of sustainability.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Criteria</strong>&ndash;describes how an institution earns points for the credit.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Applicability</strong>&ndash;indicates which institutions&rsquo; STARS scores will be affected by their responses to the credit. Some credits do not apply to some types of institutions. For example, credits involving residence halls do not apply to institutions that do not have residence halls.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Scoring</strong>&ndash;explains how points are allocated for the credit.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Reporting Fields</strong>&ndash;lists the fields that appear within the Reporting Tool for each credit. Some fields are required while others are listed as optional if the institution wishes to provide additional information.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Timeframe</strong>&ndash;describes the time period from which data should be drawn. For some credits, particularly those that are based on the presence of a policy or program, institutions should report on current practices (i.e. status at the time of reporting). Other credits, particularly those based on quantitative performance, require historical performance data, typically drawn from a one-year period.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Sampling and Data Standards</strong>&ndash;provides guidelines on when institutions may use a representative sample to measure performance and when samples are prohibited.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/2.0/stars_2.0_credit_checklist.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 2.0 Credit Checklist</a>&nbsp;(pdf) provides a quick snapshot of the credits included in STARS 2.0. Data collected for each STARS credit is documented in the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/report/stars-reporting-tool.html\" target=\"_self\">STARS Reporting Tool</a>, which is only available to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/celebrate/current-participants.html\" target=\"_self\">current STARS Participants</a>. Current STARS Participants registered under a previous version of STARS may&nbsp;<a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/report/data-migration.html\" target=\"_self\">migrate data</a>&nbsp;to the current version.</p>\r\n<h3>Credit Development</h3>\r\n<p>STARS credits were initially developed in large part by reviewing campus sustainability&nbsp;assessments, sustainability reports from businesses, and other sustainability rating and&nbsp;ranking systems. <span><span>The current version of STARS incorporates feedback and suggestions from hundreds of diverse stakeholders and experts. </span></span>For more information see <a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/historic-documents.html\" target=\"_self\">previous versions of the STARS Technical Manual</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">Credits vary in the number of points they are worth. Points were allocated by a panel of&nbsp;STARS Steering Committee members and AASHE staff using the following considerations:</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">To what extent does achievement of the credit ensure that people (students,&nbsp;employees and/or local community members) acquire the knowledge, skills, and&nbsp;dispositions to meet sustainability challenges?</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">To what extent does achievement of the credit contribute to:</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 60px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">a. human and&nbsp;ecological health and mitigate negative environmental impacts?</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 60px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">b. secure livelihoods,&nbsp;a sustainable economy and other positive financial impacts?</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 60px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">c. social justice,&nbsp;equity, diversity, cooperation, democracy and other positive social impacts?</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">3. To what extent are the positive impacts associated with achievement of the credit not&nbsp;captured in other STARS credits?</span></p>\r\n<h3>Impact vs. Difficulty</h3>\r\n<p>As these questions indicate, the focus in allocating points was on the impact, not the difficulty,&nbsp;of earning the credit. Some sustainability initiatives may be very difficult to implement but&nbsp;yield negligible impacts. Conversely, some generally easier projects have significant impacts.&nbsp;Assigning points based on the difficulty of earning a credit would create a perverse incentive&nbsp;for institutions to focus on the difficult projects or initiatives, which may not have the most&nbsp;meaningful impact.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Given the diversity of higher education institutions, each STARS credit should be appropriate&nbsp;for most institution types. In order to accommodate this diversity, some STARS credits do not&nbsp;include detailed specifications but are instead flexible or open. In other cases, credits include&nbsp;an applicability criterion, so that the credits only apply to certain types of institutions. By&nbsp;following this approach, institutions are not penalized when they do not earn credits that they&nbsp;could not possibly earn due to their circumstances.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Additionally, STARS is designed to incorporate the full spectrum of sustainability&nbsp;achievement, and upper levels of achievement represent highly ambitious, long-term goals.&nbsp;Therefore there are some credits for which few, if any, institutions will achieve full points currently.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Lastly, to help ensure that the system works as intended, AASHE strived to ensure that each&nbsp;credit was objective, measurable, and actionable.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>',1,'technical-manual','',NULL,'2013-09-09 12:16:26'),
	(0,'Register for STARS','2013-07-30 12:35:26',93,'<p><span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>With the launch of STARS 2.0, AASHE is excited to announce different levels of access that will dramatically improve the ease of campus sustainability reporting worldwide. These levels of access are based on participant feedback, and will allow institutions to report and share their campus sustainability data.</span></p>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<table>\r\n<colgroup><col width=\"*\"></col><col width=\"135\"></col><col width=\"141\"></col></colgroup> \r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Full Access for </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>12 months*</span></p>\r\n<br /><span>&nbsp;</span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>$1,400</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>($500 discount for AASHE Members = $900)</span><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Basic Access for</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>12 months</span></p>\r\n<br /><span>&nbsp;</span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>No Cost &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>REGISTER HERE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>REGISTER HERE</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Benefits</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Measure your institution&rsquo;s current sustainability performance </span><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Create a baseline for continuous improvement toward sustainability </span><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Streamline your sustainability reporting efforts by sharing STARS reporting data with other organizations (e.g. Sierra Magazine and The Princeton Review) </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Compare and learn from other institutions of similar type and demographic </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Gain global recognition for your sustainability efforts as a STARS rated institution</span><span> </span><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Celebrate your rating with access to STARS promotional tools </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Monitor your progress toward a STARS rating with automated point calculation</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Excel and PDF exports of STARS data</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Access to all public STARS data through the STARS API</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>?</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>*Institutions that purchase a STARS subscription within 90 days after their previous subscription has expired are eligible for a 50% discount.</span></p>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Global Access</span><span> &ndash; After a successful pilot period, institutions outside of U.S. and Canada are now able to register for basic and full access to &nbsp;STARS.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">Top 5 Reasons to Register<br /></span></strong><em><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">As heard from STARS Participants:</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span></em><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">1. &ldquo;The biggest benefit of STARS was that it has </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">generated new ideas</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">. Given that STARS is so widely used, the credits we were not able to attain are looked at as suggestions that we hope to implement in the future.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">2. &ldquo;It has </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">opened lines of communication</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"> and has </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">expanded sustainability understanding</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"> across campus.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>3. &ldquo;</span><span> </span><span>It is a great benefit to have </span><span>a uniform method for recording and reporting data regularly</span><span>.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>4. &ldquo;Due to administrative changes at the institution, it was very difficult to generate momentum and interest, however, the results of the data collection will be </span><span>used to draft a Sustainability Strategic Plan</span><span> which will fulfill the requirements of the College Strategic Plan.&rdquo; </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>5. &ldquo;The most important benefit was pedagogical. We look forward to continuing to use STARS as </span><span>a central part of our environmental studies and sustainability capstone courses</span><span>.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">How do recent changes affect me?</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">My institution is already participating in STARS.<br /></span></strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">Institutions that have a current STARS subscription&nbsp;<span><span>will not need to re-register. An institution with a STARS subscription will retain all the benefits above.<br /></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">My institution previously used </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">is already using</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"> the Campus Sustainability Data Collector.<br /></span></strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">An institution with an expired STARS subscription, or one previously using the CSDC, will retain Basic Access to the STARS Reporting Tool and also have the option to submit their data as a STARS Reporter. Institutions with Basic Access to the STARS Reporting Tool will have the option to purchase a subscription for Full Access at any time.</span></p>\r\n<span> </span></span></p>\r\n<p><span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>My institution is an International Pilot Participant.<br /></strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">All STARS International Pilot Participants will automatically be registered as STARS Participants under the Basic Access option and will have the option to share their data publicly as STARS Reporters. Global participants may purchase a Full Access STARS subscription at any time.</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Not sure where your institution currently stands with STARS? Complete the <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/cfm/eligibility-inquiry/\" target=\"_self\">Eligibility Inquiry Form</a> and you\'ll receive a response from the AASHE staff. All other inquiries about STARS may be directed to stars@aashe.org.</em><span></span></p>\r\n<div><span><br /></span></div>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>\r\n<div><span><br /></span></div>\r\n</span>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><span><span><br /></span></span></span></p>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p><span><br /></span></p>',1,'register-stars','',NULL,'2013-09-13 11:53:30'),
