	(100,'Previous Publications','2013-08-01 09:30:39',113,'<h2>STARS Quarterly Review</h2>\r\n<p>In 2012, AASHE published STARS data in a quarterly format, through the STARS Quarterly Review (SQR). Each edition of the SQR tells a story of sustainability in higher education based on data submitted in STARS Reports. AASHE expects to publish an annual STARS report in late-summer 2013. For questions, comments, or to submit thoughts and ideas for upcoming STARS publications, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">stars@aashe.org</a>.</p>\r\n<h3><a name=\"fall2012\" target=\"_self\"></a><a name=\"winter2012\" target=\"_self\"></a>WINTER 2012</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_winter_2012-final.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"STARS Quarterly Review: Winter 2012\" onclick=\"_gaq.push([\'_trackEvent\', \'Publications\', \'Download\', \'STARS Quarterly Review Winter 2012\']);\"><img src=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_winter_2012-cover_final.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Winter 2012 SQR cover\" width=\"259\" height=\"335\" align=\"left\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_winter_2012-final.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"Winter SQR\">Winter 2012 SQR</a>:&nbsp;<em>Recap &amp; A Look Ahead</em>,&nbsp;reviews recent developments related to the evolving concept of global campus sustainability and introduces changes that can be expected for STARS in 2013.</p>\r\n<p>Universidad de Monterrey (Mexico) is highlighted as the first STARS International Pilot participant to submit a STARS report and earn a rating. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>As STARS matures, more institutions are submitting multiple reports and using STARS as a tool for continuous improvement. Four institutions have been highlighted for recent advancements and initiatives identified in their most recent STARS reports.</p>\r\n<p>Closing out the year, this edition looks at changes that can be expected for STARS in 2013, with descriptions of new credits proposed for the launch of STARS 2.0 slated for release in 2013.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3><a name=\"fall2012\" target=\"_self\"></a>FALL 2012</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_fall_2012-final.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"STARS Quarterly Review: Fall 2012\" onclick=\"_gaq.push([\'_trackEvent\', \'Publications\', \'Download\', \'STARS Quarterly Review Fall 2012\']);\"><img src=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_fall_2012-cover_final.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Fall 2012 SQR cover\" width=\"259\" height=\"335\" align=\"left\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_fall_2012-final.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"Fall SQR\">Fall 2012 SQR</a>:&nbsp;<em>The Role of Institutional Diversity</em>,&nbsp;explores how the diversity of STARS institutions has changed over time and how participation in STARS according to institution type compares to U.S. demographics. Findings in this review suggest that the institutional characteristics that make higher education institutions distinct also play a role in how campuses are advancing sustainability.&nbsp;Particularly compelling is how NCAA conference rivalry is furthering sustainability on campuses.&nbsp;With 6 institutions highlighted,&nbsp;this&nbsp;issue covers data from reports submitted through September 1, 2012. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3><a name=\"summer2012\" target=\"_self\"></a>Summer 2012</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_summer_2012-final.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"STARS Quarterly Review: Summer 2012\" onclick=\"_gaq.push([\'_trackEvent\', \'Publications\', \'Download\', \'STARS Quarterly Review Summer 2012\']);\"><img src=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_summer_2012-cover.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Summer 2012 SQR cover\" width=\"259\" height=\"335\" align=\"left\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_summer_2012-final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summer 2012 SQR</a>: <em>Innovations in Campus Sustainability</em>, &nbsp;explores the critical linkages between education, innovation, and sustainability. &nbsp;This issue highlights new and ground-breaking practices within the Innovation (IN) category of STARS,&nbsp;focusing on the unique solutions within higher education that positively impact current and future generations. &nbsp; With 11 institutions highlighted,&nbsp;this&nbsp;issue covers data from reports submitted through June 1, 2012. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3><a name=\"spring2012\" target=\"_self\"></a>Spring 2012</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_spring_2012_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"STARS Quarterly Review: Spring 2012\" onclick=\"_gaq.push([\'_trackEvent\', \'Publications\', \'Download\', \'STARS Quarterly Review Spring 2012\']);\"><img src=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_spring_2012-cover.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Spring 2012 SQR cover\" width=\"259\" height=\"335\" align=\"left\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/sqr_spring_2012_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Spring 2012 SQR</a>: <em>Framing Campus Sustainability</em>,&nbsp;features stories that frame the evolving concept of sustainability in higher education. &nbsp;Included in this issue are a snapshot of ratings-to-date, a focus on credits within the Operations (OP) category, and insights into how institutions are defining and interpreting the evolving concepts of sustainability. &nbsp;Highlighting AASHE\'s direction of serving as a thought leader to advance sustainability, this issue covers data from reports submitted through March 1, 2012.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Spring 2011</h3>\r\n<p>The Association for the Advanc<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/stars_annual_review_2010.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"STARS: A Year in Review\"><img src=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/stars_annual_report_cover.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"2010 STARS Annual Report Cover\" width=\"302\" height=\"351\" align=\"left\" /></a>ement  of Sustainability in Higher Education (AASHE) released its first annual  \"<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/stars_annual_review_2010.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"STARS: A Year in Review\">STARS: A Year in Review</a>\" on April 14, 2011. This report details the sustainability efforts found in the inaugural submissions to the Sustainability Tracking, Assessment, Rating &amp; System (STARS), such as sustainability research opportunities, sustainable dining efforts, and campus-wide social justice initiatives.</p>\r\n<p>Thirty-seven <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/institutions/\" target=\"_self\">institutions </a>submitted their STARS Reports in time for  inclusion in the review. There are more than 200 additional institutions  participating in STARS that will be submitting reports for a rating in  the coming year.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The STARS annual review provides a wealth of information about the  state of campus sustainability,&rdquo; said AASHE Executive Director Paul  Rowland. &ldquo;Case studies, best practices, exemplary programs, and  interesting facts can all be found in the document. We hope that it will  inspire continued growth of sustainability efforts in higher  education.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>In addition to a broad range of information provided in the  institutional reports submitted by STARS Participants, &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/stars_annual_review_2010.pdf\" target=\"_self\" title=\"STARS: A Year in Review\">STARS: A Year in  Review</a>&rdquo; captures the insights and knowledge gained by those  institutions during the reporting process. Of particular note are the  following findings:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Of the first 37 submissions, which came from a variety of  institution types, eight earned a Gold Rating, 19 earned Silver, nine  earned Bronze, and one earned a Reporter Rating.</li>\r\n<li>Seven of the eight STARS Gold institutions scored more than 17 of  the 18 possible points in the Co-Curricular Education subcategory, which  focuses on non-academic programming that supports sustainability  learning.</li>\r\n<li>On average, 58% of the applicable points in the water subcategory were earned by STARS Participants.</li>\r\n<li>Ten institutions earned 100% of the points available in both the  Diversity and Affordability subcategory and the Coordination and  Planning subcategory, which together include a total of 13  sustainability indicators.</li>\r\n<li>A total of 71 sustainability innovations were reported (nearly two per institution)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The STARS Program provides ongoing opportunities for institutions to   participate.&nbsp; Institutions that are ready to <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/get-involved/registration.html\" target=\"_self\">register</a> may do so  online.&nbsp; More information about the STARS program can be obtained by  browsing the <a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/\" target=\"_self\">website</a>, reviewing the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_overview.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Overview presentation</a> (pdf) or  contacting us at <a href=\"mailto:stars@aashe.org\" target=\"_self\">stars@aashe.org</a>.</p>',1,'previous-publications','',NULL,'2013-08-08 12:50:13'),
	(300,'Correcting Mistakes','2013-08-01 09:59:33',114,'<p>Realize you\'ve made a mistake when documenting data in the STARS Reporting Tool <em>after </em>you\'ve submitted a STARS Report? &nbsp;Don\'t worry, correcting a mistake post-submission is simple.</p>\r\n<h3>1. Submit a Data Corrections Request</h3>\r\n<p>Any individual designated as an \'Administrative\' user in the STARS Reporting Tool may correct errors in a previously submitted STARS Report by submitting a Data Corrections Request. To submit a Data Corrections Request, simply navigate to the <span>the credit to be updated in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report on the STARS website and click on the icon (</span><img src=\"http://stars.aashe.org/media/static/images/note_edit.png\" border=\"0\" align=\"bottom\" /><span>) next to that credit to open the Data Corrections Request form.</span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><span>An institution may make corrections to its STARS Report with no charge up to a year after the STARS submission is received by AASHE. After that time, any institution-requested corrections require a processing fee of $150 per correction.</span></span><br /></span></p>\r\n<h3><span>2. Requests Reviewed by AASHE&nbsp;</span></h3>\r\n<p>AASHE will review the submitted form to ensure the information reflects a legitimate correction (as opposed to, for example, an update). Corrections will then be made to the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report. The corrected information in the institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will include a date stamp and note that explains the reason for the change and will be publicly available. The details of this process are explained in the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Correcting Mistakes in the Reporting Tool_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Policy for Correcting Mistakes in the Reporting Tool</a>.</p>\r\n<h3>3. Data Corrections &amp; Scoring</h3>\r\n<p><span><span>It is important to note that data corrections can impact STARS scores for rated institutions. </span><span>The process for making corrections to an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report will be the same even if the change results in a new rating level. </span></span></p>\r\n<h3>4. Reporting Erroneous Data</h3>\r\n<p>The information in an institution\'s STARS Report is self-reported and is not verified by AASHE or a third party. The&nbsp;<a href=\"/institutions/inquiry/\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry Form</a>&nbsp;is available for individuals who wish to report erroneous data they have discovered within an institution&rsquo;s STARS Report.&nbsp;Once the form has been completed and submitted, the individual&rsquo;s comments will be sent directly to the STARS Liaison assigned to that institution as well as to the STARS team.&nbsp; In submitting a STARS Submission Accuracy Inquiry,&nbsp;the questioner has the option to remain anonymous to the institution.&nbsp;&nbsp;A representative of the STARS Team&nbsp;will follow up with the institution to determine if a data correction is needed.&nbsp; For more information, please review the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/submission_review_policy_june_2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">STARS Submission Review Policy</a>.</p>',1,'correcting-mistakes','',NULL,'2013-09-09 12:45:28'),
	(0,'History','2013-08-08 10:10:39',116,'<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>[PREFER TO REPLACE WITH A TIMELINE VISUAL]</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">In August 2006, the </span><a href=\"http://www2.aashe.org/heasc/\" target=\"_self\">Higher Education Associations Sustainability Consortium</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (HEASC), an informal network of higher education associations with a commitment to sustainability, issued a </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/documents/Rating/HEASCcall.pdf\" target=\"_self\">call for a campus sustainability rating system</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf). The statement described a system that \"would of necessity address all the dimensions of sustainability (health, social, economic and ecological) and all the sectors and functions of campus, including curriculum, facilities, operations, and collaboration with communities.\" HEASC called for \"AASHE to convene all relevant stakeholders in a collaborative process to develop such a system.\"</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Over the next year and a half, AASHE gathered feedback from workshop participants at several campus sustainability conferences and events. These discussions provided the groundwork for the first publicly available draft version, </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/documents/stars/STARS0.4.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><span>STARS 0.4</span></a><span> (pdf), released in September 2007. Experts from throughout the sustainability and higher education communities provided feedback on the draft system.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>AASHE processed this feedback to develop the Pilot version of STARS, released in two phases in 2008. </span><a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/stars-pilot-project.html\" target=\"_self\"><span>Nearly 70 colleges and universities</span></a><span> participated in the pilot project. These institutions tested the system &ndash; from gathering data to reporting results &ndash; and provided </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_Pilot_Results.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><span>extensive feedback about their experiences</span></a><span> (pdf). While the pilot project was underway, AASHE released another draft version, </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/documents/stars/STARS_0.5.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><span>STARS 0.5</span></a><span> (pdf), which again generated thoughtful </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/documents/stars/STARS_0.5_Feedback.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><span>feedback and suggestions</span></a><span> (pdf) from diverse higher education stakeholders.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://stars.aashe.org/pages/about/3993/?root_category=about\" target=\"_self\"><span>STARS 1.0</span></a><span> incorporated feedback, suggestions, and lessons learned from the three-year development process. STARS 1.1 and 1.2, the next two versions, incorporated minor substantive changes to the system based on needs from the higher education community. &nbsp;While STARS is the most thoroughly vetted and extensively tested campus sustainability framework for higher education institutions, there is still plenty of room for improvement. To that end, we plan to continue improving the system over time. STARS 2.0, the current version of STARS, is intended to stimulate, not end, the conversation about how to measure and benchmark sustainability in higher education. AASHE welcomes your feedback and participation in continuing to refine and shape the system.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>View a </span><a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/engage/timeline.html\" target=\"_self\"><span>timeline</span></a><span> showing the history and development of STARS.</span></p>',0,'history','',NULL,'2013-08-28 12:52:09'),
	(0,'Historic Documents','2013-08-08 10:13:21',117,'<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">Before launching the </span><a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/report/technical-manual.html\" target=\"_self\">current version of STARS</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">, AASHE released several earlier drafts for public comment. Key documents from throughout the STARS development process are posted below.</span></p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS 1.x</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span><span>AASHE launched the STARS 1.0 Early Release in September 2009 that included all of the credits but limited supporting information as a sneak peek to those interested in participating. AASHE made minor administrative updates after releasing this document that were incorporated in STARS 1.0 that launched in January 2010.</span></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_1.0_Early_Release_Technical_Manual.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.0 Early Release Technical Manual </a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">(pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">The STARS Technical Manual </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Technical_Manual_Changes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Record of Changes</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) details the minor differences between the Early Release edition and the January 2010 updated edition.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span><span><span>AASHE incorporated additional support information in the Technical Manual after the early release and launched the completed STARS 1.0 Technical Manual, website, and Reporting Tool in January 2010. AASHE issued an Administrative Update to this version in June 2010 and November 2011.</span></span> </span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_1.0_Technical_Manual.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.0 Technical Manual </a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">(January 2010 edition) (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Technical_Manual_Changes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Record of Changes</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) details the changes between the January 2010 and June 2010 edition</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/STARS_1.0.1_Technical_Manual.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.0 Technical Manual</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (June 2010 edition) (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/1.0.2_Record_of_Changes_05Nov10.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Record of Changes</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) details the changes between the June 2010 and November 2010 edition.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">STARS 1.0 Credit Checklist (</span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_1.0_Credit_List.pdf\" target=\"_self\">pdf</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> or </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_1.0_credit_list.xls\" target=\"_self\">xls</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>AASHE launched STARS 1.1 Administrative Update One in February 2011. This Administrative Update contains basic system maintenance changes to STARS 1.1, such as additional language to clarify credits and correction of typographical errors.</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_administrative_update_one_technical_manual.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.1 Administrative Update One Technical Manual</a> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/1.1_record_of_changes_final.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Record of changes</a> (pdf) details the changes between STARS 1.0 Administrative Update Two and STARS 1.1 Administrative Update One.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">STARS 1.1 Credit Checklist (</span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_credit_checklist.pdf\" target=\"_self\">pdf</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> or </span><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.1_credit_checklist.xls\" target=\"_self\">xls</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>AASHE released STARS 1.2 in February 2012. &nbsp;Like the changes from STARS 1.0 to STARS 1.1, this version of STARS includes minor updates to the system.</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.2_technical_manual.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 1.2 Technical Manual</a> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/stars_1.2_record_of_changes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Record of changes</a> (pdf) details the changes between STARS 1.1 Administrative Update One and STARS 1.2</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/1x-organization.html\" target=\"_self\">Learn how credits were organized and weighed</a> in each of the STARS 1.x versions of the Technical Manual.</p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS International Pilot Project</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The STARS International Pilot project took place from October 2011 and December 2013. &nbsp;All institutions of higher education outside of the US and Canada were welcome to register for the current STARS system, completed a STARS Report as a STARS Reporter, and give feedback on how STARS could be shaped to better fit international needs. Learn more about the <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/guidelines_for_stars_international_pilot.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS International Pilot</a> (pdf).</p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS Pilot Project</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The STARS pilot project took place from February 2008 to January 2009 and involved <a href=\"http://stars.aashe.org/pages/history/4597/?root_category=about#Institutions_Participating_in_the_STARS_Pilot\" target=\"_self\"><span>66 institutions</span></a> in the US and Canada. <a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/stars-pilot-project.html\" target=\"_self\">Learn additional details about the STARS Pilot Project</a> including the overall approach, participating institutions, and notes from conference calls. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_Pilot_Phase_One_Guide.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Guide to Pilot Phase One</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_Pilot_Phase_Two.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Guide to Pilot Phase Two</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_Pilot_Results_0.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Pilot Project Results</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS 0.x</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>AASHE released STARS 0.5 in April 2008.</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_0.5.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 0.5</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/documents/stars/STARS_0.5_Feedback.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Feedback on STARS 0.5</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>AASHE released STARS 0.4 in September 2007. </span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS0.4.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS 0.4</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS0.4commentsv2.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Comments on STARS 0.4</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS0.4_survey_responses.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Responses to STARS 0.4 Survey</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf)</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://stars-facelift.dev.aashe.org/pages/stars-04-conference-calls.html\" target=\"_self\">Notes from conference calls about STARS 0.4</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>Predecessors of STARS</span></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/CSRS_0.1.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Campus Sustainability Rating System (CSRS) 0.1</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) - released January 2007</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/CSRSproposal.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Original Campus Sustainability Rating System Proposal</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) - released January 2007</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">Sustainability in Higher Education Assessment Framework (SHEAF) - a 2006 project that grew to become STARS</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>Summary Notes from Conference Workshops</span></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/SSCC07_workshop_summary.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Smart and Sustainable Campuses Conference</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) - April 2007</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/RMSS_workshop_summary.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Rocky Mountain Sustainability Summit</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) - Feb. 2007</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>Other Historic Documents</span></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_Governance_Structure.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Governance Structure</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) - Jan. 2010</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/HEASCcall.pdf\" target=\"_self\">HEASC Call for a Campus Sustainability Rating System</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (pdf) - Aug. 2006</span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/blog/podcast-all-about-stars\" target=\"_self\">Listen to the STARS podcast</a><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> (18 minutes) -- Feb. 2008</span></li>\r\n</ul>',1,'historic-documents','',NULL,'2013-09-09 09:28:21'),
	(0,'1.x organization','2013-08-08 10:41:31',118,'<h3>How Credits Were Developed and Weighted for STARS 1.x</h3>\r\n<div style=\"float: right; padding: 5px; margin: 12px; width: 200px; border: 1px solid #aaa;\">\r\n<p><em><strong>Gatekeeper Questions</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em>What does it take for a credit to be included in STARS? Each STARS credit was vetted using the following questions:</em></p>\r\n<p><em>1. Does the credit speak to improved environmental, social, and/or financial impacts?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>2. Is the credit relevant and meaningful for diverse institutions?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>3. If the credit is based on the presence of a strategy, is a performance-based indicator not available or appropriate?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>4. Is the credit measurable, objective, and actionable?</em></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>STARS credits were developed in large part by reviewing campus sustainability assessments, sustainability reports from businesses, and other sustainability rating and ranking systems. For STARS 1.0 the initial credits from the STARS Pilot were revised or eliminated and new credits were added based on feedback from hundreds of diverse stakeholders and experts. In addition, STARS credits were vetted using four criteria.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>In order to be included, each credit must lead to improved environmental, social, and/or economic performance by colleges and universities. While the sphere of impact may vary each credit should indicate a movement toward sustainability.</li>\r\n<li>Given the diversity of higher education institutions, each STARS credit should be appropriate for most institution types. In order to accommodate this diversity, some STARS credits do not include detailed specifications but are instead flexible or open. In other cases, credits include an applicability criterion, so that the credit only applies to certain types of institutions.</li>\r\n<li>STARS strives to prioritize performance over strategy when possible. Performance credits are based on measurements of sustainability performance while strategy credits focus on approaches or processes that can help improve an institution\'s performance. In many instances, however, measurable, meaningful, and fairly comparable performance indicators could not be identified, so a strategy-based credit was used. As a result, both strategy and performance credits have a place in the system.</li>\r\n<li>AASHE strived to ensure that each credit was objective, measurable, and actionable.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Points were allocated using the following considerations:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>To what extent does the credit contribute to improved environmental impacts?</li>\r\n<li>To what extent does the credit contribute to improved financial impacts?</li>\r\n<li>To what extent does the credit contribute to improved social impacts?</li>\r\n<li>To what extent are there educational benefits associated with the achievement of this credit?                                      \r\n<ul type=\"circle\">\r\n<li>How many people are impacted (breadth)?&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>How deeply are people impacted (depth)?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Tier One and Tier Two Credits</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n<p>Each STARS credit that meets these four criteria listed above (see also &ldquo;gatekeeper questions&rdquo; textbox) is classified as Tier One or Tier Two.&nbsp; The differences between Tier One and Tier Two credits are outlined below:</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=\"center\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\"><strong>Tier One</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\"><strong>Tier Two</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Strive to capture measurable outcome</li>\r\n<li><span>Vary in the number of points they are worth</span></li>\r\n<li><span><span>Grouped in a subcategory (e.g. Curriculum) within a category (e.g. Education &amp; Research)</span><br /></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"height: 0px;\">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Acknowledge strategies and tend to have a smaller impact than Tier One credits</li>\r\n<li><span>Promote strategies whose benefits are already captured by a Tier One credit</span></li>\r\n<li><span><span>Worth 0.25 points each</span><br /></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>',1,'1x-organization','',NULL,'2013-08-08 10:41:31'),
