	(0,'STARS Pilot Project','2013-08-08 11:14:53',119,'<p><a href=\"#STARS_Pilot_Project\" target=\"_self\">STARS&nbsp;Pilot Project</a><br /> <a href=\"#Institutions_Participating_in_the_STARS_Pilot\" target=\"_self\">Institutions Participating in the STARS Pilot</a><br /> <a href=\"#STARS_Pilot_Project_Conference_Calls_\" target=\"_self\">STARS Pilot Project Conference Calls</a></p>\r\n<h2><strong><a name=\"STARS_Pilot_Project\" target=\"_self\"></a></strong>Approach</h2>\r\n<p>The STARS pilot project took place from February 2008 to January 2009. Institutions that participated in the pilot tested the system and provided feedback to AASHE to help shape future versions of STARS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The STARS pilot project took place in two phases. A phased approach helped to moderate the workload for participating institutions. It also allowed AASHE to solicit another round of feedback about some sections included in STARS before asking schools to gather data.</p>\r\n<p>Phase One of the STARS pilot started in February 2008. Phase One covers the Operations category and about half of the Administration and Finance category. View <span class=\"spaced_list\"><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/documents/stars/STARS_Pilot_Phase_One_Guide.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Guide to Pilot Phase One</a> (pdf)</span>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>STARS Pilot Phase Two started in September 2008.&nbsp; Phase Two covers the Education and Research category and remaining credits in the Administration and Finance category, as well as Tier Two Credits and Innovation Credits.&nbsp; View <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/documents/stars/STARS_Pilot_Phase_Two.pdf\" target=\"_self\">STARS Guide to Pilot Phase Two</a> (pdf).</p>\r\n<h2>Results</h2>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/STARS_Pilot_Results.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Sustainability Tracking, Assessment &amp; Rating System Pilot Project Results</a> (pdf) is a detailed summary of results and feedback received during the pilot project.</p>\r\n<h2>Student Research</h2>\r\n<p>Kyle Murphy, a student at The Evergreen State College, coordinated his institution\'s participation in the STARS Pilot Project and wrote his Master\'s thesis about lessons learned from that experience.&nbsp; He writes:</p>\r\n<address>This research focused on three main questions with respect to Evergreen&rsquo;s use of the STARS tool: (a) Is STARS an effective tool for use at Evergreen (did the framework address issues important to Evergreen, did it meet the criteria of an ideal assessment framework, and what are the advantages and disadvantages), (b) Does the STARS process lead to organizational learning, and (c) What STARS reveal about Evergreen&rsquo;s commitment to sustainability. Using a case study research design, I took a multi-disciplinary approach to the data collection for STARS implementation. Through my research I found that STARS is an effective tool to evaluate sustainability at Evergreen, which led to organizational learning, and highlighted Evergreen&rsquo;s complex and dynamic commitment to sustainability.</address>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/documents/STARS/Murphy_STARS_Evergreen.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Thesis presentation</a> (pdf)<br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/files/resources/student-research/2009/Murphy_K MESThesis_2009.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Thesis full text</a> (pdf)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong><a name=\"Institutions_Participating_in_the_STARS_Pilot\" target=\"_self\"></a>Institutions Participating in the STARS Pilot</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Institutions are listed below according to their basic Carnegie Classification and student population.</p>\r\n<h2><strong>Associate\'s Colleges</strong></h2>\r\n<p><strong>Large (more than 12,500 students)</strong><br /> Cedar Valley College &ndash; Lancaster, Texas<br /> De Anza Community College &ndash; Cupertino, California<br /> Eastfield College &ndash; Mesquite, Texas <br /> Grand Rapids Community College &ndash; Grand Rapids, Michigan<br /> Monroe Community College &ndash; Rochester, New York<br /> Mountain View College &ndash; Dallas, Texas <br /> North Lake College &ndash; Irving, Texas<br /> Richland College &ndash; Dallas, Texas<br /> Santa Barbara City College &ndash; Santa Barbara, California<br /> Santa Fe Community College &ndash; Santa Fe, New Mexico</p>\r\n<p><strong>Medium (3,000 to 12,500 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Delta College &ndash; University Center, Michigan<br /> Northwest State Community College &ndash; Archbold, Ohio</p>\r\n<p><strong>Districts</strong></p>\r\n<p>Dallas County Community College District &ndash; Dallas, Texas<br /> Eastern Iowa Community College District &ndash; Davenport, Iowa</p>\r\n<h2>Baccalaureate Colleges</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Small (fewer than 3,000 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>College of St. Benedict &ndash; St. Joseph, Minnesota<br /> Dickinson College &ndash; Carlisle, Pennsylvania<br /> Gustavus Adolphus College &ndash; St. Peter, Minnesota<br /> Middlebury College &ndash; Middlebury, Vermont<br /> Mount Union College &ndash; Alliance, Ohio<br /> Northland College &ndash; Ashland, Wisconsin<br /> Randolph College &ndash; Lynchburg, Virginia<br /> St. John\'s University &ndash; Collegeville, Minnesota<br /> University of Minnesota, Morris &ndash; Morris, Minnesota<br /> Williams College &ndash; Williamstown, Massachusetts</p>\r\n<h2>Canadian Institutions</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Large (more than 12,500 students)</strong><br /> Concordia University &ndash; Montreal, Quebec<br /> McGill University &ndash; Montreal, Quebec<br /> University of British Columbia &ndash; Vancouver, British Columbia</p>\r\n<p><strong>Medium (3,000 to 12,000 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Acadia University - Wolfville, Nova Scotia</p>\r\n<h2>Doctorate-granting Universities</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Large (more than 12,500 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Arizona State University &ndash; Tempe, Arizona<br /> Ball State University &ndash; Muncie, Indiana<br /> Colorado State University &ndash; Fort Collins, Colorado<br /> Illinois State University &ndash; Normal, Illinois<br /> Iowa State University &ndash; Ames, Iowa<br /> New York University &ndash;New York, New York<br /> Portland State University &ndash; Portland, Oregon<br /> Rutgers, The State University of New Jersey &ndash; New Brunswick, New Jersey<br /> Syracuse University &ndash; Syracuse, New York<br /> University of California, San Diego &ndash; San Diego, California<br /> University of California, Santa Barbara &ndash; Santa Barbara, California<br /> University of Central Florida &ndash; Orlando, Florida<br /> University of Colorado at Boulder &ndash; Boulder, Colorado<br /> University of Florida &ndash; Gainesville, Florida<br /> University of Illinois at Chicago &ndash; Chicago, Illinois<br /> University of Kansas &ndash; Lawrence, Kansas<br /> University of New Hampshire &ndash; Durham, New Hampshire<br /> University of Texas at Austin &ndash; Austin, Texas<br /> Worcester Polytechnic Institute &ndash; Worcester, Massachusetts</p>\r\n<p><strong>Medium (3,000 to 12,000 students)</strong><br /> Case Western Reserve University &ndash; Cleveland, Ohio<br /> Emory University &ndash; Atlanta, Georgia</p>\r\n<p><strong>Small (fewer than 3,000 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>State University of New York, College of Environmental Science &amp; Forestry &ndash; Syracuse, NY</p>\r\n<h2>Master\'s Colleges and Universities</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Large (more than 12,500 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Appalachian State University &ndash; Boone, North Carolina<br /> Boise State University &ndash; Boise, Idaho<br /> California State University, Chico &ndash; Chico, California<br /> California State University, Sacramento &ndash; Sacramento, California<br /> Eastern Kentucky University &ndash; Richmond, Kentucky<br /> Grand Valley State University &ndash; Allendale, Michigan<br /> University of Nebraska at Omaha &ndash; Omaha, Nebraska</p>\r\n<p><strong>Medium (3,000 to 12,000 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Florida Gulf Coast University &ndash; Fort Meyers, Florida<br /> Pacific Lutheran University &ndash; Tacoma, Washington<br /> Santa Clara University &ndash; Santa Clara, California<br /> Seattle Pacific University &ndash; Seattle, Washington<br /> The Evergreen State College &ndash; Olympia, Washington<br /> University of Colorado at Colorado Springs &ndash; Colorado Springs, Colorado<br /> University of Wisconsin - River Falls &ndash; River Falls, Wisconsin</p>\r\n<p><strong>Small (fewer than 3,000 students)</strong><br /> Monterey Institute of International Studies &ndash; Monterey, California</p>\r\n<h2>Special Focus Institutions</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Small (fewer than 3,000 students)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology &ndash; Terre Haute, Indiana</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong><a name=\"STARS_Pilot_Project_Conference_Calls_\" target=\"_self\"></a>STARS Pilot Project Conference Calls </strong></h1>\r\n<p>Throughout the pilot period, AASHE conducted a series of conference calls focused on the categories covered by STARS. The calls provided an opportunity for institutions participating in the pilot project to ask questions, provide feedback, and share strategies for gathering data and achieving the credits. Calls were open only to institutions participating in the STARS pilot project.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Pilot Phase Two Calls</h2>\r\n<p><strong>1. Co-Curricular Education and Faculty and Staff Development and Training Call</strong><br /> Thursday, September 18th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Daylight Time</em><br /> <em><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/CoCurric_FacStaffDev_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a> </em>(pdf)  <br /> <br /> <strong>2. Curriculum Call </strong><br /> Thursday, September 25th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m.<em> Pacific Daylight Time<br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/Curriculum_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a> </em>(pdf) <br /> <br /> <strong>3. Research Call </strong><br /> Thursday, October 2nd, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Daylight Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/Research_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf) <br /> <strong><br /> 4. Community Relations and Partnerships Call </strong><br /> Thursday, October 9th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m.<em> Pacific Daylight Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/Community_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf) <br /> <strong><br /> 5. Diversity, Access, and Affordability Call </strong><br /> Thursday, October 16th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m.<em> Pacific Daylight Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/Diversity_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf) <br /> <br /> <strong>6. Human Resources Call </strong><br /> Thursday, October 23rd, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m.<em> Pacific Daylight Time</em><br /> <em>Call did not occur due to low attendance <br /> </em><br /> <strong>7. Trademark Licensing and Innovation Credits Call </strong><br /> Thursday, October 30th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Daylight Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/TM_Innovation_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf)</p>\r\n<h2><br /> Pilot Phase One Calls</h2>\r\n<p><strong>1. Kick-Off Call</strong><br /> Monday, February 11th, 2008, 9:00 &ndash; 10:00 a.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time<br /> </em>Monday, February 11th, 2008, 12:00 &ndash; 1:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> Tuesday, February 12th, 2008, 10:30 &ndash; 11:30 a.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <em><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/KickOff_Calls_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a></em> (pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>2. Buildings Call (OP Credits 1 &ndash; 4)</strong><br /> Tuesday, February 19th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <em><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Call_Notes_Buildings.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a></em> (pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>3. Dining Services Call (OP Credits 5 &ndash; 7)</strong><br /> Tuesday, February 26th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Call_Notes_Dining_Services.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>4. Energy and Climate Call (OP Credits 8 &ndash; 11)</strong><br /> Tuesday, March 4th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Call_Notes_Energy_Climate.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>5. Grounds Call (OP Credits 12 &ndash; 13)</strong><br /> Tuesday, March 11th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Call_Notes_Grounds.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>6. Materials, Recycling, and Waste Minimization Call (OP Credits 14 &ndash; 18)</strong><br /> Tuesday, March 18th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time<br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Call_Notes_Materials_Recycling.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a> </em>(pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>7. Purchasing Call (OP Credits 19 &ndash; 24)</strong><br /> Tuesday, March 25th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <em><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Purchasing_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a> </em>(pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>8. Transportation Call (OP Credits 25 &ndash; 28)</strong><br /> <em><strong>*</strong></em>Thursday, April 3rd, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. Pacific Standard Time<br /> <em><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Transportation_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a> </em>(pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>9. Investment Call (AF Credits 1 &ndash; 5)</strong><br /> Tuesday, April 8th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <em><a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Investment_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">Summary notes</a> </em>(pdf)</p>\r\n<p><strong>10. Planning and Sustainability Infrastructure Call (AF Credits 6 &ndash; 11)</strong><br /> Tuesday, April 15th, 2008, 11:00 a.m. &ndash; 12:00 p.m. <em>Pacific Standard Time</em><br /> <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/Plan_Inf_Call_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\"><em>Summary notes</em></a> (pdf)</p>\r\n<h2>Other</h2>\r\n<p>In addition to the calls, pilot participants gathered at the AASHE 2008 conference. Notes from that meeting are <a href=\"http://www.aashe.org/stars/pilot/documents/AASHE_08_Conf_STARS_Notes.pdf\" target=\"_self\">available here</a> (<em>pdf</em>).</p>',1,'stars-pilot-project','',NULL,'2013-08-08 11:14:53'),
	(0,'Free Tier','2013-08-09 13:47:58',122,'<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">In 2012, AASHE launched two initiatives to facilitate higher education sustainability reporting and data sharing:</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\"> </span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">The Campus Sustainability Data Collector (CSDC) , a free tool for U.S. institutions to share data with organizations such as Sierra Magazine and The Princeton Review</span></li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">The STARS International Pilot, a</span><span style=\"font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.5;\">n opportunity for colleges and universities located outside the U.S. and Canada to participate in STARS at no cost to share feedback and make suggestions for improvements to the system.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span> </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>In response to participant feedback and to make STARS accessible to all higher education institutions, AASHE is fully integrating the CSDC and international participation into STARS to coincide with the launch of STARS 2.0.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span><br /></span></p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>What Does it Look Like?</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Very little will change. There will be a unified STARS Reporting Tool with two levels of access; &nbsp;institutions will be able to decide at which level they want to participate:</span></p>\r\n<table style=\"border: 1px solid #000000;\" border=\"1\" frame=\"border\">\r\n<colgroup><col width=\"116\"></col><col width=\"253\"></col><col width=\"254\"></col></colgroup> \r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span><strong>Level of Access</strong><span> </span></span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>STARS Subscription (paid)</span><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Basic Access &nbsp;(free)</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Features/Benefits</strong></p>\r\n<br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Continuous access to the STARS Reporting Tool</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Multiple user accounts</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Ability to share data with third parties</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Submitted data posted on STARS website</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Access to Resources</span><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Full access to Data Displays </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Public recognition as a STARS subscriber</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Automated scoring</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Benchmarking opportunities</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Data exports</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>API access</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Single-click export of STARS Reports to Snapshots</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Continuous access to the STARS Reporting Tool</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Multiple user accounts</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Ability to share data with third parties</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Submitted data posted on STARS website</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Access to Resources (AASHE members)</span></p>\r\n<br /><span>&nbsp;</span><br /><span>&nbsp;</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Levels of Recognition Available</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A participant that earns the points to do so may receive a </span><span>STARS Bronze, Silver, Gold or Platinum rating</span><span>. Submitting for a rating will make data and scores public. </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>All participants have the option to submit data to AASHE as STARS Reporters, regardless of access level. Doing so will make data public, but not scores.</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><span> <br /> </span></p>\r\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\"><span>Registration and Participation</span></h3>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>My institution is already participating in STARS</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Institutions that have registered for STARS will not need to re-register. An institution with a STARS subscription will retain all the benefits associated with the subscription, including the ability to pursue a STARS rating. An institution with an expired subscription will retain basic access to the Reporting Tool and also have the option to submit their data as a STARS Reporter.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>My institution is already using the Campus Sustainability Data Collector</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Institutions that have registered for the CSDC will not need to re-register for STARS. All CSDC Survey Respondents will automatically be registered as STARS Participants under the basic access option and will have the option to share their data publicly as STARS Reporters. Participants may purchase a STARS subscription from within the Reporting Tool at any time.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>My institution is an International Pilot Participant</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Institutions that have registered for the STARS International Pilot will not need to re-register for STARS. All pilot participants will automatically be registered as STARS Participants under the basic access option and will have the option to share their data publicly as STARS Reporters. Participants may purchase a STARS subscription from within the Reporting Tool at any time.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>My institution has not registered</strong></p>\r\n<p><span>Institutions that have never registered for STARS, the CSDC, or the International Pilot can either </span><span>register</span><span> for STARS under the basic access option or purchase a STARS subscription. A STARS subscription may also be purchased at any time from within the STARS Reporting Tool.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>